# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1988-winter-olympics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The **1896 Summer Olympics**, officially known as the **Games of the I Olympiad**, and commonly known as **Athens 1896** (Greek: Αθήνα 1896), were the first international Olympic Games held in modern history.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Organised by the International Olympic Committee (IOC), which had been created by French aristocrat Pierre de Coubertin, the event was held in Athens, Greece, from 6 to 15 April 1896.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Fourteen nations (according to the IOC, though the number is subject to interpretation) and 241 athletes (all males; this number is also disputed) took part in the games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Participants were all European or living in Europe, with the exception of the United States team, and over 65% of the competing athletes were Greek.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Winners were given a silver medal, while runners-up received a copper medal.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Retroactively, the IOC has designated the top three finishers in each event as gold, silver, and bronze medalists.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Ten of the 14 participating nations earned medals.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] On April 6, 1896, American James Connolly became the first Olympic medalist in more than 1,500 years, competing in the triple jump.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold medals, 11, while host nation Greece won the most medals overall, 47.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The highlight for the Greeks was the marathon victory by their compatriot Spyridon Louis.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The most successful competitor was German wrestler and gymnast Carl Schuhmann, who won four events.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Athens had been chosen to stage the inaugural modern Games during a congress organised by Coubertin in Paris on 23 June 1894, during which the IOC was also created.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The main venue was the Panathenaic Stadium, where athletics and wrestling took place; other venues included the Neo Phaliron Velodrome for cycling and the Zappeion for fencing.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony was held in the Panathenaic Stadium on 6 April, during which most of the competing athletes were aligned on the infield, grouped by nation.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] After a speech by the president of the organising committee, Crown Prince Constantine, his father officially opened the Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, nine bands and 150 choir singers performed an Olympic Hymn, composed by Spyridon Samaras and written by Kostis Palamas.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Olympics were regarded as a great success.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Games had the largest international participation of any sporting event to that date.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Panathenaic Stadium overflowed with the largest crowd ever to watch a sporting event.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] After the Games, Coubertin and the IOC were petitioned by several prominent figures, including Greece's King George and some of the American competitors in Athens, to hold all the following Games in Athens.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] However, the 1900 Summer Olympics were already planned for Paris, and, with the exception of the Intercalated Games of 1906, the Olympics did not return to Greece until the 2004 Summer Olympics, 108 years later.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] During the 19th century, several small-scale sports festivals across Europe were named after the ancient Olympic Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The 1870 Olympics at the Panathenaic stadium, which had been refurbished for the occasion, had an audience of 30,000 people.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Pierre de Coubertin, a French pedagogue and historian, adopted William Penny Brookes's idea to establish a multi-national and multi-sport event (even though the ancient games only allowed male athletes of Greek origin to participate).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In 1890, Coubertin wrote an article in *La Revue Athlétique*, which espoused the importance of Much Wenlock, a rural market town in the English county of Shropshire.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] It was here that, in October 1850, the local physician William Penny Brookes founded the Wenlock Olympian Games, a festival of sports and recreations that included athletics and team sports like cricket, football and quoits.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Coubertin also took inspiration from earlier Greek games organised under the name of Olympics by businessman and philanthropist Evangelis Zappas in 1859, 1870 and 1875.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Athens Games were funded by the legacies of Zappas and his cousin Konstantinos Zappas and by George Averoff who had been requested by the Greek government to sponsor the second refurbishment of the Panathenaic Stadium.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Greek government did this despite the cost of refurbishing the stadium in marble already being funded in full by Evangelis Zappas forty years earlier.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] On 18 June 1894, Coubertin organised a congress at the Sorbonne, Paris, to present his plans to representatives of sports societies from 11 countries.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Following his proposal's acceptance by the congress, a date for the first modern Olympic Games was discussed; Coubertin suggested that the Games be held concurrently with the 1900 Universal Exposition of Paris.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Concerned that a six-year waiting period might lessen public interest, congress members opted to hold the inaugural Games in 1896.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] With a date established, members of the congress discussed the selection of a host city.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] It is unknown how Athens was chosen: Coubertin and Demetrius Vikelas's descriptions of the selection process contradicted the congress's official minutes.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Most accounts state that several congressmen first proposed London, but Coubertin dissented.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] After a brief discussion with Vikelas, who represented Greece, Coubertin suggested Athens.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Vikelas made the Athens proposal official on 23 June; since Greece had been the original home of the Olympics, the congress unanimously approved the decision.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Vikelas was then elected the first president of the newly established International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The return of the Olympic Games to Greece was well-received by the Greek public, media, and royal family.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Crown Prince conferred their patronage to the games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] However, the country had financial troubles and was in political turmoil.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The country's prime minister frequently alternated between Charilaos Trikoupis and Theodoros Deligiannis during the last years of the 19th century.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] This instability caused Trikoupis and Stephanos Dragoumis, the president of the Zappas Olympic Committee, which had attempted to organise a series of national Olympiads, to believe that Greece could not host the event.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In late 1894, the organising committee under Stephanos Skouloudis presented a report that the cost of the Games would be three times higher than originally estimated by Coubertin.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] They concluded the Games could not be held and offered their resignation.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] With the prospect of reviving the Olympic games in doubt, Coubertin and Vikelas commenced a campaign to increase the Olympic movement's popularity.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] On 7 January 1895 Vikelas announced that crown prince Constantine would assume the presidency of the organising committee.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] His first responsibility was to raise the funds necessary to host the Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] He relied on the patriotism of the Greek people to motivate them to provide the required finances.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Constantine's enthusiasm increased contributions from the Greek public, raising 330,000 drachmas (equivalent to $1,106,157,688 in 2025).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] A special set of postage stamps was commissioned; the sale of which raised 400,000 drachmas (equivalent to $1,340,797,197 in 2025).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] At the request of Constantine, businessman George Averoff agreed to pay for the restoration of the Panathenaic Stadium.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] As a tribute to his generosity, a statue of Averoff was constructed and unveiled on 5 April 1896 outside the stadium.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The IOC's first regulation, voted on in 1894, was to allow only amateur athletes to participate in the Olympic Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The various contests were thus held under amateur regulations, except for fencing matches.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The rules and regulations were not uniform, so the Organising Committee chose among the codes of the various national athletic associations.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The jury, the referees and the game director bore the same names as in antiquity (*Ephor*, *Helanodic* and *Alitarc*).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Prince George acted as final referee; according to Coubertin, "his presence gave weight and authority to the decisions of the ephors".
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Women could not compete at the 1896 Summer Olympics because Coubertin felt that their inclusion would be "impractical, uninteresting, unaesthetic and incorrect".
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Seven venues were used for the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Panathenaic Stadium was the main venue, hosting four of the nine sports contested.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The town of Marathon hosted the marathon event and the individual road race events.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Fencing was held at the Zappeion, sport shooting at Kallithea, and tennis at the Athens Lawn Tennis Club.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Swimming was held in the Bay of Zea; it was selected because the organizers of the Games wanted to avoid spending money on constructing a special-purpose swimming venue.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Four of the 1896 venues were reused as competition venues for the 2004 Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The velodrome would be renovated into a football stadium in the 1960s and was known as Karaiskakis Stadium.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] This venue was renovated in 2003 for use as a football venue for the 2004 Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] During the 2004 Games, Panathinaiko Stadium hosted the archery competitions and was the finish line for the athletic marathon event.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The city of Marathon itself served as the starting point for both marathon events during the 2004 Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Zappeion served as the first home of the organizing committee (ATHOC) for the 2004 Games from 1998 to 1999, and served as the press center for non-accredited media during those Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] On Easter Monday 6 April (25 March according to the Julian calendar used in Greece until 1923) the games of the First Olympiad were officially opened.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Panathenaic Stadium was filled with between 16,000 and 80,000 spectators, including King George I of Greece, his wife Olga, and other members of the royal family.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Most of the competing athletes were aligned on the infield, grouped by nation.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, nine bands and 150 choir singers performed an Olympic Hymn, composed by Spyridon Samaras, with words by poet Kostis Palamas.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The first announcements regarding the sporting events to be held featured sports like equestrian and cricket, but these plans were not finalised, and these sports did not make the final program for the Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Football is sometimes listed as having been an exhibition or demonstration sport, although whether a football match actually occurred is disputed.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Rowing and sailing events were cancelled on the planned days of competition: sailing due to a lack of special boats in Greece and no foreign entries, and rowing due to poor weather.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Summer Olympics programme featured 9 sports encompassing 10 disciplines and 43 events.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The athletics events had the most international field of any of the sports.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The major highlight was the marathon, held for the first time in international competition.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Spyridon Louis, a previously unrecognised water carrier, won the event to become the only Greek athletics champion and a national hero.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Although Greece had been favoured to win the discus and the shot put, the best Greek athletes finished second to American Robert Garrett in both events.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] No world records were set, as few top international competitors had elected to compete and the curves of the track were very tight, making fast times in the running events virtually impossible.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Thomas Burke of the United States won the 100-meter race in 12.0 seconds and the 400-meter race in 54.2 seconds.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Burke was the only one who used the "crouch start" (putting his knee on soil), confusing the jury.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Chile claims one athlete, Luis Subercaseaux, who competed for the nation at the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Subercaseaux's results are not listed in the official report, though that report typically includes only winners and Subercaseaux won no medals.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] He was entered to compete in the 100m, 400m and 800m events but is usually listed as a no show.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] An appraisal of a photo of series 2 of the 100 meters sprint, performed by facial recognition experts of the Chilean forensic police, concluded that Subercaseaux was one of the participants.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The day after the official marathon, Stamata Revithi ran the 40-kilometer course in 5 hours 30 minutes, finishing outside Panathinaiko Stadium.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Some authors, who believe that "Melpomene" and Revithi are the same person, attribute to the latter the more favorable time of 4+1⁄2 hours.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] She was denied entry into the official race as the 1896 Olympics excluded women from competition.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The cycling competitions used the rules of the International Cycling Association.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The newly built Neo Phaliron Velodrome hosted the track cycling events.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Only one road event was held, a race from Athens to Marathon and back (87 kilometres).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In the track events, the best cyclist was Frenchman Paul Masson, who won the one lap time trial, the sprint event, and the 10,000 meters.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In the 100 kilometres event, Masson entered as a pacemaker for his compatriot Léon Flameng.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Flameng won the event, after a fall and after stopping to wait for his Greek opponent Georgios Kolettis to fix a mechanical problem.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Austrian fencer Adolf Schmal won the 12-hour race, which was completed by only two cyclists, while the road race event was won by Aristidis Konstantinidis.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The fencing events were held in the Zappeion, which, built with money Evangelis Zappas had given to revive the ancient Olympic Games, had never seen any athletic contests before.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Unlike other sports (in which only amateurs were allowed to take part at the Olympics), professionals were authorised to compete in fencing, though in a separate event.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] These masters professionals were considered gentlemen athletes, just like the amateurs.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Four events were scheduled, but the épée event was cancelled for unknown reasons.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The foil event was won by a Frenchman, Eugène-Henri Gravelotte, who beat his countryman, Henri Callot, in the final.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The other two events were won by Greek fencers: Ioannis Georgiadis won the sabre event, and Leonidas Pyrgos won the masters foil, becoming the first Greek Olympic champion in the modern era.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The gymnastics competition was carried out on the infield of the Panathinaiko Stadium.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Germany sent an 11-man team, which won five of the eight events, including both team events: in the team event on the horizontal bar, the German team was the only entry.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Three Germans added individual titles: Hermann Weingärtner won the horizontal bar event, Alfred Flatow won the parallel bars, and Carl Schuhmann, who also won the wrestling event, won the vault.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Louis Zutter, a Swiss gymnast, won the pommel horse, while Greeks Ioannis Mitropoulos and Nikolaos Andriakopoulos were victorious in the rings and rope climbing events, respectively.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] A regatta of sailing boats was on the program of the Games of the First Olympiad for 31 March 1896 (Julian calendar).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The event was cancelled: the official English report blamed a lack of specialty boats had not been provided while the German version also cited a lack of foreign competitors.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Rowing races were scheduled for the next day, 1 April 1896 (Julian).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Poor weather caused the event to be postponed to 3 pm and German Berthold Küttner stated that he and Adolf Jäger had lined up for the start of the double sculls, the first event to take place.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The event was further postponed to the next day, but the German team still completed the event in the bad weather: they were presented with the winners medal upon the completion of their row.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The next day, the event was formally cancelled when the weather worsened.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee does not recognize Küttner's recollection of the events.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Held at a range at Kallithea, the shooting competition consisted of five events—two using a rifle and three with a pistol.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The first event, the military rifle, was won by Pantelis Karasevdas, the only competitor to hit the target with all of his shots.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The second event, for military pistols, was dominated by two American brothers: John and Sumner Paine.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] They became the first siblings to finish first and second in the same event.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] To avoid embarrassing their hosts, the brothers decided that John would withdraw from the free pistol event.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Sumner Paine won that event, becoming the first relative of an Olympic champion to become Olympic champion himself.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Paine brothers did not compete in the 25-meter pistol event, as the event judges determined that their weapons were not of the required calibre; Ioannis Phrangoudis won the event.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The final event, the free rifle, could not be completed due to darkness and was finalised the next morning, with Georgios Orphanidis winning the competition.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The swimming competition was held in the open sea because the organizers had refused to spend the money necessary for a specially constructed stadium.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Nearly 20,000 spectators lined the Bay of Zea off the Piraeus coast to watch the events.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The water in the bay was cold, and the competitors suffered during their races.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] There were three open events (men's 100-metre freestyle, men's 500-metre freestyle, and men's 1200 metre freestyle), in addition to a special event open only to Greek sailors, all of which were held on the same day (11 April).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] For Alfréd Hajós of Hungary, this meant he could only compete in two of the events, as they were held too close together, which made it impossible for him to adequately recuperate.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Nevertheless, he won the two events in which he swam, the 100 and 1200 meter freestyle.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Hajós later became one of only two Olympians to win a medal in both the athletic and artistic competitions, when he won a silver medal for architecture in 1924.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The 500-meter freestyle was won by Austrian swimmer Paul Neumann, who defeated his opponents by more than a minute and a half.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Although tennis was already a major sport by the end of the 19th century, none of the top players turned up for the tournament in Athens.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The competition was held at the courts of the Athens Lawn Tennis Club, and the infield of the velodrome used for the cycling events.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] John Pius Boland, who won the event, had been entered in the competition by a fellow-student of his at Oxford; the Greek, Konstantinos Manos.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] As a member of the Athens Lawn Tennis sub-committee, Manos had been trying, with the assistance of Boland, to recruit competitors for the Athens Games from among the sporting circles of Oxford University.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In the first round, Boland defeated Friedrich Traun, a promising tennis player from Hamburg, who had been eliminated in the 100-meter sprint competition.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Boland and Traun decided to team up for the doubles event, in which they reached the final and defeated their Greek opponents after losing the first set.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The sport of weightlifting was still young in 1896, and the rules differed from those in use today.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Competitions were held outdoors, in the infield of the main stadium, and there were no weight limits.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The first event was similar in style to what is now known as the "clean and jerk".
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Two competitors stood out: Briton Launceston Elliot and Viggo Jensen of Denmark.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Both of them lifted the same weight, but the jury, with Prince George as the chairman, ruled that Jensen had done so in a better style.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The British delegation, unfamiliar with this tie-breaking rule, lodged a protest.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The lifters were eventually allowed to make further attempts, but neither lifter improved, and Jensen was declared the champion.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Elliot got his revenge in the one hand lift event, which was held immediately after the two-handed one.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Jensen had been slightly injured during his last two-handed attempt and was no match for Elliot, who won the competition easily.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Greek audience was charmed by the British victor, whom they considered very attractive.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] A curious incident occurred during the weightlifting event: a servant was ordered to remove the weights, which appeared to be a difficult task for him.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Prince George came to his assistance; he picked up the weight and threw it a considerable distance with ease, to the delight of the crowd.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] No weight classes existed for the wrestling competition, held in the Panathenaic Stadium, which meant that there would only be one winner among competitors of all sizes.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The rules used were similar to modern Greco-Roman wrestling, although there was no time limit, and not all leg holds were forbidden (in contrast to current rules).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Apart from the two Greek contestants, all the competitors had previously been active in other sports.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Weightlifting champion Launceston Elliot faced gymnastics champion Carl Schuhmann.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The latter won and advanced into the final, where he met Georgios Tsitas, who had previously defeated Stephanos Christopoulos.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Darkness forced the final match to be suspended after 40 minutes; it was continued the following day, when Schuhmann needed only fifteen minutes to finish the bout.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] On the morning of Sunday 12 April (or 31 March, according to the Julian calendar then used in Greece), King George organised a banquet for officials and athletes (even though some competitions had not yet been held).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] During his speech, he made clear that, as far as he was concerned, the Olympics should be held in Athens permanently.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The official closing ceremony was held the following Wednesday after being postponed from Tuesday due to rain.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Again, the royal family attended the ceremony, which was opened by the national anthem of Greece and an ode composed in ancient Greek by George S.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Robertson, a British athlete and scholar.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, the king awarded prizes to the winners.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Unlike today, the first-place winners received a silver medal, an olive branch and a diploma, while runners-up received a copper medal, a laurel branch and a diploma.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Third place winners did not receive a prize.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Some winners also received additional prizes.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Spyridon Louis received a cup from Michel Bréal, a friend of Coubertin, who had conceived the marathon event.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Louis then led the medalists on a lap of honour around the stadium, while the Olympic Hymn was played again.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The King then formally announced that the first Olympiad was at an end and left the Stadium, while the band played the Greek national hymn and the crowd cheered.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Like the Greek king, many others supported the idea of holding the next Games in Athens; most of the American competitors signed a letter to the Crown Prince expressing this wish.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Coubertin, however, was heavily opposed to this idea, as he envisioned international rotation as one of the cornerstones of the modern Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] According to his wish, the next Games were held in Paris, although they would be somewhat overshadowed by the concurrent Universal Exposition.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The concept of national teams was not a major part of the Olympic movement until the Intercalated Games 10 years later, though many sources list the nationality of competitors in 1896 and give medal counts.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] There are significant conflicts with regard to which nations competed.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee gives a figure of 14, but does not list them.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Different sources provide differing lists of nations; some exclude countries like Chile and Bulgaria, but the IOC lists competitors from both countries.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Egypt is also sometimes included due to the participation of Dimitrios Kasdaglis; however, the IOC classifies him as a Greek athlete.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Belgium and Russia had entered the names of competitors, but no athletes from these countries competed.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] National Olympic Committees did not yet exist.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Ten of the fourteen participating nations earned medals, in addition to two medals won by mixed teams (teams made up of athletes from multiple nations).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The IOC has retroactively assigned gold, silver and bronze medals to the three best placed athletes in each event to comport with more recent traditions.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In this regard, five of the bronze medalists at the Games are unknown: two in swimming and three in gymnastics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold medals (11), while host nation Greece won the most medals overall (47), as well as the most silver (18) and bronze (19) medals, finishing with one fewer gold medal than the United States.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The **1900 Summer Olympics** (French: *Jeux olympiques d'été de 1900*), today officially known as the **Games of the II Olympiad** (*Jeux de la IIe olympiade*) and also known as **Paris 1900**, were an international multi-sport event that took place in Paris, France, from 14 May to 28 October 1900.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] No opening or closing ceremonies were held.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] At the Olympic Congress of 1894, which convened in the Sorbonne building, Pierre de Coubertin proposed that the Olympic Games should take place in Paris in 1900.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] However, the delegates to the conference were unwilling to wait six years and lobbied to hold the first games in 1896.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A decision was made to hold the first Olympic Games in 1896 in Athens and have Paris host the second Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Games were held as part of the 1900 Exposition Universelle (World's Fair).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In total, 1,226 competitors took part in 19 different sports.[note1] This number relies on certain assumptions about which events were and were not "Olympic".
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Many athletes, some of whom had won events, were unaware they had competed in the Olympic Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Women took part in the games for the first time, with sailor Hélène de Pourtalès, born Helen Barbey in New York City, becoming the first female Olympic champion.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The decision to hold competitions on a Sunday brought protests from many American athletes, who traveled as representatives of their colleges and were expected to withdraw rather than compete on their religious day of rest.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Most of the winners in 1900 did not receive medals but were given cups or trophies.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Professionals competed in fencing, as was tradition, and Albert Robert Ayat (France), who won the épée for amateurs and masters, was awarded a prize of 3,000 F (equivalent to €13,896 in 2025).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Some events were contested for the only time in the history of the Games, including angling, motor racing, ballooning, cricket, croquet, Basque pelota, 200m swimming obstacle race and underwater swimming.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] This was also the only Olympic Games in history to use live animals (pigeons) as targets during the shooting event.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The host nation of France fielded 72% of all athletes (720 of the 997) and won the most gold, silver and bronze medal placings.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] U.S. athletes won the second-most in each while fielding the fifth-most participants, 75.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] British athletes won the third-most in each while fielding the second most participants, 102.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Games were held as part of the 1900 Exposition Universelle.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Baron de Coubertin believed this would help public awareness of the Olympics and submitted elaborate plans to rebuild the ancient site of Olympia, complete with statues, temples, stadia, and gymnasia.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The director of the Exposition Universelle, Alfred Picard, thought holding an ancient sport event at the Exposition Universelle was an "absurd anachronism".
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] After thanking de Coubertin for his plans, Picard filed them away and nothing more came of it.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A committee was formed for the organization of the Games, consisting of some of the more able sports administrators of the day, and a provisional program was drawn up.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Sports to be included at the games were track and field athletics, swimming, wrestling, gymnastics, fencing, French and British boxing, river and ocean yacht racing, cycling, golf, lifesaving, archery, weightlifting, rowing, diving, and water polo.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] British and Irish sports associations and several influential American universities and sports clubs announced their desire to compete.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Competitors from Russia and Australia also confirmed their intentions to travel to Paris.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] On 9 November 1898, the Union des Sociétés Françaises de Sports Athlétiques ("Union of the French Societies for Athletic Sports" or USFSA) announced that it would have the sole right to any organized sport held during the World's Fair.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] It was an empty threat, but Viscount Charles de La Rochefoucauld, the nominated head of the organizing committee, stepped down rather than be embroiled in the political battle.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC ceded control of the Games to a new committee to oversee every sporting activity connected to the 1900 Exposition Universelle.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Alfred Picard appointed Daniel Mérillon, the head of the French Shooting Association, as president of this organization in February 1899.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Mérillon published an entirely different schedule of events, which resulted in many of those who had made plans to compete with the original program withdrawing and refusing to deal with the new committee.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Between May and October 1900, the new organizing committee held many sporting activities alongside the Paris Exposition.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The press reported competitions variously as "International Championships", "International Games", "Paris Championships", "World Championships" and "Grand Prix of the Paris Exposition".
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] These poorly organized games, along with those of 1904, were termed decades later by several historians "The Farcical Games".
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Years later, many competitors were unaware that they had competed in the Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] While there is an Official Report of these Games, complete records of results do not exist.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] De Coubertin commented later to friends, "It's a miracle that the Olympic Movement survived that celebration".
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Before July 2021, the IOC had never decided which events were "Olympic".
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In fact, Pierre de Coubertin had ceded that entire determination to the organizers.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC webpage for the 1900 Summer Olympics affirms a total of 95 medal events.[note1] Weightlifting and wrestling were dropped since the 1896 Summer Olympics, while 12 new sports were added.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Among the sports below, only croquet was not an international competition, being contested by French players only.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] 14 venues were used at the 1900 Summer Olympics to host 20 sports.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Map of Paris with Olympic venues marked.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Map of France with Olympic venues marked.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The standard of competition at the Games was variable.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Despite a poor-quality track, a strong contingent of top-class American collegiate athletes ensured the track and field competitions were of the highest quality.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The tennis gold medalists were all former Wimbledon champions; swimming and fencing events were of a good standard; and even polo, a minority sport for the social elite, was well represented by some of the best players in the game.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Other sports were noticeably weak in both quality and depth.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Only athletics, swimming and fencing had competitors from more than ten nations.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The history of the archery competition at the 1900 Olympics is one of confusion.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC currently lists six events with Olympic status, but a case has been made that as many as eight other events equally deserve to be considered part of official Olympic history.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] About 150 archers competed in the six events that later had official status conferred.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] However, as many as 5,000 were involved in archery competition in conjunction with the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Belgian Hubert Van Innis took two gold medals and one silver and would add to his tally twenty years later in Antwerp.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The track and field events were held at the home of the Racing Club de France at the Croix-Catelan stadium in Bois de Boulogne.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] No track was laid and races took place on an uneven field of grass littered with trees.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Additional events were held for professionals and a series of handicap races also took place.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] These are not considered official Olympic events.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In the seven events contested over 400 metres or less, the United States took 13 out of a possible 21 medals.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Athletes from Columbia University, Princeton University and the University of Pennsylvania all won gold medals.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Indeed, two would-be dentists from the University of Pennsylvania were among the stars of the Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Alvin Kraenzlein won 4 individual gold medals, a feat that has never repeated, while Walter Tewksbury took five medals including two golds.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The hurdles in the 400 m hurdle race were 30-foot (9.1 m)-long telegraph poles arranged on the track and the race, uniquely in Olympic competition, had a water jump on the final straight.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Adolphe Klingelhoeffer, who had Brazilian citizenship in 1900, competed for France in three events.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] United States dominance in sprinting was matched in the longer track races by United Kingdom.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Only George Orton, who won Canada's first Olympic title in the shorter of the two steeplechases, ruined a perfect record for the British.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Orton won his title less than an hour after placing third in the 400-metre hurdles.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The most contentious of all the events in these Games began and ended in the Bois de Boulogne.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Intended to follow the track of the old city wall, the course was poorly marked out and runners often got lost and had to double back on themselves before continuing.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] On some parts of the course, runners had to contend with distractions from cars, bicycles, pedestrians and animals.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Arthur Newton of the United States finished fifth but stated he had not been passed by any other runner during the race.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Another American, Richard Grant, claimed he was run down by a cyclist as he made ground on the leaders.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] French honour seemed to have been satisfied when Michel Théato crossed the finish line and a military band struck up La Marseillaise.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] However, modern research has revealed that Théato was born in Luxembourg and maintained Luxembourgian citizenship throughout his life.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Hungarian discus thrower Rudolf Bauer was the only non-American crowned as Olympic Champion.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] American domination was even greater in the field events than the track events, with outstanding performances coming from Ray Ewry and Irving Baxter.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Ewry started his Olympic career with a sweep of the three standing jumps, while Baxter finished second to Ewry three times and won both the regular high jump and pole vault.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Meyer Prinstein became the first Jewish Olympic gold medalist in the triple jump.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The chistera form of the game was played at this, the sport's only appearance at full Olympic level.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Two pairs entered and the Spanish partnerships of Amezola and Villota became their nations' first Olympic champions.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The mano form of the game and a chistera tournament for professional players were contested unofficially.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] After the withdrawal of teams from the Netherlands and Belgium, only two teams played in the cricket tournament.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A team made up of players from the Albion Cricket Club and the Standard Athletic Club, two Paris clubs consisting almost exclusively of British expatriates, played a touring team from the southwest of England.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Devon and Somerset Wanderers were no more than a team of competent club cricketers (made up from Blundells School old boys and members of Castle Cary Cricket Club), and only Montagu Toller and Alfred Bowerman were deemed good enough to play at county level for Somerset.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The game was played before a small crowd at the Vélodrome de Vincennes.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] An emphatic second innings bowling performance from Toller captured victory for the visitors as time appeared to be running out for them.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] If the French had held out for five more minutes the game would have been a draw.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Knowledge of the game would have been lost but for the forethought of John Symes, a member of the victorious team, who kept a scorecard in his own writing.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The croquet tournament was notable as it marked the first appearance of women at Olympic level.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Madame Desprès, Madame Filleul-Brohy and Mademoiselle Ohier were eliminated in the first round of competition.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A single paying spectator attended the tournament, an elderly English gentleman who travelled from Nice for the early stages.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] An unofficial two-ball handicap competition was also held.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] This was also the only Olympiad where croquet was part of the official programme, though there was the variant called roque at the 1904 Summer Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The home nation won six of the nine medals available, including one that was initially awarded to Great Britain until this was reversed in 2024.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A number of unofficial events were held for both amateurs and professionals.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Equestrian sport made its debut at the Olympic Games with three jumping events being held, plus two other events.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Italian rider Gian Giorgio Trissino won a gold and a silver.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] He narrowly missed making Olympic history by winning two medals in the same event.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Competing with two different horses in the high jump, he jointly won the gold medal and finished in 4th place on his second horse.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Nineteen nations were represented in the fencing competition, which was held in a field near the cutlery exhibit at the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] French fencers dominated the proceedings but both Cuba and Italy also took titles.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The early rounds of the foil competitions were judged on style rather than the actual result of the contest.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] This meant that some fencers were eliminated without losing a contest while others were defeated and still progressed to the next rounds.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The first football champions at the Olympics were the London amateurs of Upton Park F.C.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A crowd of around 500 spectators saw them defeat their French rivals.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Margaret Ives Abbott, a student of art from Chicago, played in and won a nine-hole golf tournament on an October Tuesday in Paris.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] She died in 1955 without being aware that the tournament was part of the Olympic Games and she had become America's first ever female Olympic champion.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] 135 gymnasts took part in a competition that involved elements from track and field and weightlifting as well as gymnastic disciplines.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Eight separate tournaments were held in 1900 as part of the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Only the Grand Prix Internationale de l'Exposition is counted as an official medal event.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Entries were from clubs rather than countries, and the winning Foxhunters club comprised English, Irish and American players.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Mexico won its first medal in this sport, a bronze won by Guillermo Hayden Wright, Marquez de Villavieja and three brothers: Eustaquio de Escandón y Barron, Pablo de Escandón y Barron and Manuel de Escandón y Barron.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Competitions were held on the River Seine.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Following this, officials decided to run another final for the boycotting crews.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Both events are considered official Olympic competitions.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In a number of events, crews saw the advantage of having ultra-lightweight coxswains and recruited local boys for race days.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Most of these remain a mystery; some could have been under ten years old.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Three teams competed in the Rugby tournament.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A French representative team defeated a team from the German city of Frankfurt and Moseley Wanderers from England.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Moseley team had played a full game of rugby in England the day before they made the journey to Paris.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] They arrived in the morning, played the match in the afternoon and were back in their home country by the next morning.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The proposed game between the British and German sides was cancelled, and both are credited as silver medalists.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Franco-Haitian centre Constantin Henriquez become the first black gold medalist.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 sailing regatta differs from every other Olympic regatta in a number of ways.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In most classes, there were two distinct "finals", boats were assigned time handicaps according to their weight within each class and cash prizes were handed out to the winner of each race.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC initially recognized the winner of the first race in each class as Olympic champion except in the case of the 10-20 ton class, which was decided on aggregate time over three races.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] However currently the participants of both first and second races in 3 classes (0-0.5t, 1-2t and 2-3t) are present in the as medalists, so the second races in these 3 classes were recognized by the IOC, as recommended by Olympic historian Bill Mallon.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] To support the recognition of a total of 95 medal events per Mallon's suggestion, one more race in each of 2 other classes (0.5-1t and 3-10t) has been recognized by the IOC.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Thus, for five of the eight events, two gold, two silver and two bronze medals were retrospectively awarded.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Races were held at both Meulan and Le Havre and medals shared among five nations.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] France and Great Britain were the most successful of the countries involved.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A number of people named as members of medal-winning crews by the IOC have been proved not to have competed; others have their participation seriously questioned by historical research.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Switzerland's Konrad Stäheli was the outstanding marksman of the Games, taking a trio of titles and leading his country to the top of the shooting medal table.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The medals were shared between six different nations.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] There is a debate as to whether the live pigeon shooting event was a full Olympic event, Belgian Leon Lunden shot twenty-one birds on his way to the championship.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Up to thirty unofficial shooting events were also held, most involving professional marksmen.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Research has shown that one of the medal events in the IOC database (25m rapid fire pistol, also called military pistol cat.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The muddied waters of the Seine hosted the swimming events in 1900.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Run with the current, the races produced very fast times by the standards of the day.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] John Arthur Jarvis of Great Britain, Frederick Lane of Australia and the German Ernst Hoppenberg each won two titles.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Lane received a 50-pound bronze statue of a horse as a prize.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The obstacle race required both swimming underneath and climbing over rows of boats while Charles de Venville stayed submerged for over a minute to win the underwater swimming event.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A high-quality men's tournament saw three past or future Wimbledon champions reach the semi-finals.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Laurence Doherty reached the final when older brother Reggie stepped aside and let his sibling advance to the final.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The two refused to play each other in what they considered a minor tournament.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] On the 11th of July a landmark was reached in the history of the Olympic Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Charlotte Cooper, already three times Wimbledon champion, took the singles championship to become the first individual female Olympic champion, also winning the mixed doubles event.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A combined Sweden/Denmark team, made up of three competitors from each country, defeated the French team to win the title.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] One of the members of the French team was a Colombian citizen.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] They were left as the only participating teams; the United States had entered but were forced to scratch as three of their team were involved in the final of the hammer.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Edgar Aabye was a journalist covering the Games for the Danish newspaper Politiken and was asked to join the team when another puller was taken ill.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Osborne Swimming Club, representing Great Britain, were unchallenged in the tournament, scoring 29 goals and conceding only 3 in their 3 matches.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In the final, they limited the number of shots on goal to avoid humiliating their opponents.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] One of its team members, Victor Lindberg, was from New Zealand, while Thomas William Burgess of the bronze medal-winning Libellule de Paris team represented Great Britain in the swimming events.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Games were not governed by a specific Olympic organizing committee, but were instead held as an appendage to the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] An enormous number of events was held, though many fall short of the standards later required for Olympic championship status.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] After the several initial editions of the Olympic Games, decisions as to which Olympic events were termed "official" and which had "unofficial" or "demonstration" status were usually left to the Olympic organizing committees and/or the IOC.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In the early Olympic Games, however, no decision as to the official status of any event was made at the time of the Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] While a document from 1912 exists, listing results from the 1900 Games, and formed the original basis of the results of the Paris games in the IOC database, the reliability and authenticity of this paper has been questioned by Olympic historians.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Further complicating matters, the IOC has never determined which events were Olympic and which were not.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Of the three events that satisfied three criteria, only croquet has been accorded Olympic status.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In this regard, one of the ten croquet players, Marcel Haëntjens, had been believed to be Belgian, and the croquet events were thus considered as international.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Despite the Flemish name, it was discovered in recent times that Haëntjens was French.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Scholastic and military events were also held across a range of sports.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Four planned competitions were not organized due to a lack of participants: balle au tamis, field hockey, jeu de paume and lacrosse.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] According to the International Olympic Committee, 26 nations sent competitors to this edition.[note1] The concept of "national teams" chosen by National Olympic Committees did not exist at this point in time.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] When counting the number of participating countries in the early Olympic Games, the IOC does not take into account otherwise unrepresented countries whose citizens competed for other countries.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Modern research shows that at the 1900 Olympics, the athletes of at least four otherwise unrepresented countries competed for other countries in both individual and team sports.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] George Orton, gold medalist in 2500 metres steeplechase event and bronze medalist in 400 metres hurdles event, and Ronald J.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] MacDonald, both of Canada, competed for the U.S. athletics team.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Orton ran for the University of Pennsylvania and was therefore assumed to be American, but he always considered himself a Canadian.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Michel Théato, the winner of the marathon, competed for the French athletics team.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] He was a Luxembourger; however, this was only discovered decades later.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Francisco Henríquez de Zubiría of Colombia was a silver medal-winner on the French tug of war team.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Victor Lindberg of New Zealand was a gold medal-winner on the British water polo team.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC website lists all of them in the results section under their nationalities, but does not include their countries among the 26 participating countries.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Debuting nations at the games included Argentina, Belgium, Bohemia, Cuba, Haiti, India, Mexico, Netherlands, Norway, Persia, Peru, Romania, Russia and Spain.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Nations that participated in the previous games in Athens 1896 but were absent in Paris 1900 included Bulgaria and Chile.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Austria and Hungary competed as two sovereign countries.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The polity known as Austria-Hungary is mistakenly considered a single sovereign country, while in reality was two sovereign states in real union with a single monarch who was titled both emperor of Austria and king of Hungary.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] At the time, Bohemia was part of Austria, while Australia, Canada and India were all part of the British Empire.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Algeria sent four gymnasts who competed for France, while all of Ireland was considered a part of Great Britain: Irish athletes competed in athletics, polo, sailing and tennis.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Further, a Polish fencer represented Russia, a Croatian fencer represented Austria, and two Slovak athletes competed for Hungary.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The concept of "national teams" chosen by National Olympic Committees did not exist at this point in time.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Olympics is unique in being the only Olympic Games to feature rectangular medals, which were designed by Frédérique Vernon.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Gilt silver medals were awarded for 1st place in shooting, lifesaving, automobile racing and gymnastics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Whilst 2nd place silver medals were awarded in shooting, rowing, yachting, tennis, gymnastics, sabre, fencing, equestrian and athletics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] With 3rd place bronze medals being awarded in gymnastics, firefighting and shooting.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In many sports, however, medals were not awarded.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] With most of the listed prizes were cups and other similar trophies.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee has retrospectively assigned gold, silver and bronze medals to all competitors who earned 1st, 2nd and 3rd-place finishes, respectively, in order to bring early Olympics in line with current awards.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] For the first Olympic Games (until Antwerp in 1920), it is difficult to give the exact number of medals awarded to some countries, due to the fact that teams were composed of athletes from different countries.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] For Olympic Games before 1908 there is no universally accepted definition of nationality, and medal tables may vary depending on the chosen definition.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] For example, Australian Stanley Rowley competed as part of a team selected by the Amateur Athletic Association of England.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1900 Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The **1904 Summer Olympics** (officially the **Games of the III Olympiad** and also known as **St.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis 1904**) were an international multi-sport event held in St.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis, Missouri, United States, from 1 July to 23 November 1904.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Many events were conducted at what is now known as Francis Field on the campus of Washington University in St.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] This was the first time that the Olympic Games were held outside Europe.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Tensions caused by the Russo–Japanese War and difficulties in traveling to St.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis resulted in very few top-class athletes from outside the United States and Canada taking part in the 1904 Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Only 69–74 of the 651 athletes who competed came from outside North America, and only between 12 and 15 nations were represented in all.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Some events subsequently combined the U.S. national championship with the Olympic championship.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The current three-medal format of gold, silver and bronze for first, second and third place was introduced at the 1904 Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] After the first two editions of the Olympic Games were awarded to Athens and Paris, the IOC's first open bidding process was held for the 1904 Olympics at the 4th IOC Session in Paris in May 1901.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Chicago civic leaders, including University of Chicago president William Rainey Harper, formed the International Olympian Games Association in February 1901 to plan for hosting the Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Shortly before the session began, another American bid was submitted from St.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis, which was then preparing to host the Louisiana Purchase Exposition, a World's Fair in 1903.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] At the session, representatives of Chicago offered to put $100,000 (equivalent to $3,870,000 in 2025) toward the games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Unable to compete with this, all other countries withdrew their bids before the IOC voted; cities which had previously expressed interest in the 1904 games included Berlin, Copenhagen, and Stockholm.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The IOC delegates then voted between the choices of Chicago and St.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis, with Chicago winning unanimously on May 21.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis was forced to postpone its World's Fair from 1903 to 1904, it began planning athletic events that would compete directly with the Olympics in Chicago.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis and planned to hold its national championships at the World's Fair.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] In the meantime, Chicago's plans for a new stadium on the shore of Lake Michigan seating 75,000 met considerable opposition from local leaders, including Aaron Montgomery Ward, putting the centerpiece of Chicago's Olympic bid into question.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] On December 23, 1902, fearing that the dispute would permanently damage the Olympic movement, the IOC asked its members to approve, by a postal vote, the transfer of the Olympic Games to St.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] When the votes were tallied, IOC founder Pierre de Coubertin telegraphed the Chicago committee on February 10, 1903, to inform them that the Games had been moved.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Boxing, dumbbells, catch wrestling (which later became freestyle wrestling), and the decathlon made their debuts.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The swimming events were held in a temporary pond near Skinker and Wydown Boulevards, where "lifesaving demonstrations" of unsinkable lifeboats for ocean liners took place.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Chicago runner James Lightbody won the steeplechase and the 800 m and then set a natural world record in the 1500 m.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Harry Hillman won both the 200 m and 400 m hurdles and also the flat 400 m.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Sprinter Archie Hahn was champion in the 60 m, 100 m and 200 m.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] In this last race, he set an Olympic record in 21.6, a natural record that stood for 28 years.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] In the discus, after American Martin Sheridan had thrown exactly the same distance as his compatriot, Ralph Rose (39.28 m), the judges gave them both an extra throw to decide the winner.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Sheridan won the decider and claimed the gold medal.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Ray Ewry again won all three standing jumps.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The team representing Great Britain was awarded a total of two medals, both won by Irish athletes.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The top non-U.S. athlete was Emil Rausch of Germany, who won three swimming events.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Zoltán Halmay of Hungary and Charles Daniels of the United States each won two swimming gold medals.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Galt Football Club from Canada won the gold medal in football.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The organizers of the World's Fair held "Anthropology Days" on August 12 and 13.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Since the 1889 Paris Exposition, human zoos, as a key feature of world's fairs, functioned as demonstrations of anthropological notions of race, progress, and civilization.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] These goals were followed also at the 1904 World's Fair.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Fourteen hundred indigenous people from Southeast Asia, the Pacific Islands, East Asia, Africa, the Middle East, South America and North America were displayed in anthropological exhibits that showed them in their natural habitats.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Another 1600 indigenous people displayed their culture in other areas of the Louisiana Purchase Exposition (LPE), including on the fairgrounds and at the Model School, where American Indian boarding schools students demonstrated their successful assimilation.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The sporting event itself took place with the participation of about 100 paid indigenous men.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Contests included "baseball throwing, shot put, running, broad jumping, weight lifting, pole climbing, and tugs-of-war before a crowd of approximately ten thousand".
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] No women participated in Anthropology Days, though some, notably the Fort Shaw Indian School girls basketball team, did compete in other athletic events at the LPE.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] According to theorist Susan Brownell, world's fairs – with their inclusion of human zoos – and the Olympics were a logical fit at this time, as they "were both linked to an underlying cultural logic that gave them a natural affinity".
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Also, one of the original intentions of Anthropology Days was to create publicity for the official Olympic events.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The 1904 Summer Olympic program featured 16 sports encompassing 95 events in 18 disciplines.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Swimming, diving and water polo are considered three disciplines of the same sport, *aquatics*.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] In July 2021 the IOC accepted the recommendation of Olympic historian Bill Mallon regarding which sports and events should be considered as Olympic.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Boxing made its Olympic debut at the St.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The sport has since featured at every Summer Olympics, except for the 1912 Stockholm Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] While wrestling made a return, it was exclusively the newly debuted catch wrestling (which later became freestyle wrestling) as opposed to Greco-Roman style of the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Five nations were represented, with each of the 42 competitors having resided in the United States.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Later editions would have both styles of wrestling in their programs.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Basketball, hurling, American football and Gaelic football were featured as unofficial sports.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] There was a demonstration bout of women's boxing.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Baseball is also noted by the World Baseball Softball Confederation to have appeared at the Games, though it does not appear in the list compiled by Olympic historian Bill Mallon and any results are not known.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Creve Coeur Lake is located further west.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Five sports venues were used for the 1904 Summer Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The venues included Glen Echo Country Club, the first golf course constructed west of the Mississippi River, which had opened in 1901.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Three Olympic sports were hosted at Forest Park, the site of the Louisiana Purchase Exposition which was being held concurrently with the Olympics: the Life Saving Exhibition Lake at Forest Park was used for the diving, swimming, and water polo events.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Creve Coeur Lake became the first park of St.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The Lake has hosted rowing regattas since 1882 and still hosts them as of 2010.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Francis Olympic Field and Gymnasium are still in use on the Washington University in St.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] An ornamental gate commemorating the 1904 Games was constructed outside the stadium immediately after the Exposition.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] A swimming pool was added to the gymnasium in 1985.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Forest Park, constructed in 1876, is still in use as of 2021 and attracts over 12 million visitors annually.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Glen Echo Country Club remains in use as a golf course today as of 2021.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Athletes from thirteen nations competed in St.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Numbers in parentheses indicate the number of known competitors for each nation.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis in 1904, and European tensions caused by the Russo-Japanese War, only 69–74 athletes from outside North America participated in the Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] These are the nations that won medals at the 1904 Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The nationalities of some medalists were disputed, as many American athletes were recent immigrants to the United States who had not yet been granted U.S. citizenship.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] These cases saw medals credited to the United States transferred to other countries or mixed teams.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] In addition, the IOC had counted one gold, one silver, and two bronze medals won by the American fencer Albertson Van Zo Post for Cuba instead of the United States.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The IOC also had shown Charles Tatham as a Cuban medal-winner for individual fencing events (foil and épée) and American silver medalist in the team foil event, but he was an American.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] All are now credited to the United States.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The **1906 Intercalated Games** or **1906 Olympic Games** (Greek: Μεσολυμπιάδα, romanized: *Mesolympiada*, lit.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] 'Mesolympics'), held from 22 April 1906 to 2 May 1906, was an international multi-sport event that was celebrated in Athens, Greece.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] It was at the time considered to be part of the series of the Olympic Games, and was referred to as the "Second International Olympic Games in Athens" by the International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The 1906 Games is noted for its influence on the Olympic tradition and the records broken during these Games are recorded in history, but are no longer considered part of the Olympic records.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] 894 athletes from 20 nations competed in this competition.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The idea behind the Intercalated Games was to have an Olympics in Greece every four years, but this would be the first and last.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The idea was not pursued further, and is sometimes termed the "forgotten Games" in the context of the Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The next Olympic Games was the 1908 Summer Olympics in London; the next time the Olympic Games returned to Greece was 98 years later in 2004, also in Athens.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The Intercalated Olympic Games were to be a series of *International Olympic Games* halfway between what is now known as the Games of the Olympiad, old and new.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] This proposed series of Games, intercalated in the Olympic Games cycle, was always to be held in Athens and was to have equal status with the international Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] However, the only such Games was held in 1906.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] One reason for the Games in 1906 was to celebrate the tenth anniversary of the 1896 Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The first Intercalated Games had been scheduled by the International Olympic Committee in 1901 as part of a new schedule, where every four years, in between the internationally organised Games, there would be an Intermediate Games held in Athens.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] This was a compromise; after the successful Games of Athens 1896, the Greeks suggested they could organise the Games every four years.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Since they had the accommodation and had proven they could hold well-organised Games, they received substantial public support.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] However, Pierre de Coubertin, the founder of the International Olympic Committee, opposed this, as he had intended for the first Games to be in Paris in 1900.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] After Paris had lost the première Olympics, De Coubertin did not want the Games to be permanently hosted elsewhere.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The 1900 Games were overshadowed by the Exposition Universelle, whose organising committee disagreed with De Coubertin's ideas to such an extent that he resigned.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The organisation of the 1900 Games was haphazard by today's standards, and although some events, such as archery, drew widespread attention, many others were poorly attended.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Historians' opinions still differ over which events should be considered "Olympic".
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Consequently, the IOC supported the Greek idea by granting them a second series of quadrennial Games in between the first series.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] This was a departure from the ancient schedule, but it was expected that, if the ancient Greeks could keep a four-year schedule, the modern Olympic Movement could keep a two-year schedule.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] As 1902 was now too close to be logistically workable, and Greece was experiencing political and economic difficulties, the 2nd Olympic Games in Athens were scheduled for 1906, and the IOC as a whole gave Greece full support for the organisation.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Louis, Missouri were overshadowed by the Louisiana Purchase Exposition, and their organisation was even worse than that of Paris 1900, while travel difficulties meant that only 20% of the athletes were non-American; of these, half were Canadian.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] It was clear the Olympic Movement was in a dire situation and desperately needed to recapture the spirit of Athens 1896.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] It also needed to do so quickly, as to those who did not participate in St.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Louis, 1908 was a gap of eight years, by which time there would be little, if any, goodwill left for the Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] To make matters worse, Rome, the proposed host for 1908, was also planning an exhibition at the same time as the Games, which had been responsible for the failures of Paris and St.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] To the IOC, the 1906 Athens Games being just around the corner would have been a lifeline.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] While De Coubertin still opposed the idea and did not do anything more than his function required of him, the IOC as a whole gave the Greek organising committee full support for the organisation.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] These games offered Greece the huge opportunity to show that it was important to Europe's present and its past.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] It is clear from the beginning that the Olympic Games 1906 became "a grand project far beyond the status of a mere sports meeting", with new structures built to accommodate the events including the restoration of the ancient stadium in Athens.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The 1906 Games were quite successful: unlike the Games of 1900, 1904 or 1908, they were not stretched out over several months, and unlike 1900 and 1904, they were not overshadowed by an international exposition.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Their crisp implementation was most likely instrumental in the continued existence of the Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] These, along with various other changes, are now accepted as tradition.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The Games were held from 22 April to 2 May 1906, in Athens, Greece.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] They took place in the Panathenaic Stadium, which had already hosted the 1896 Games and the earlier Zappas Olympics of 1870 and 1875.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The Games excluded several disciplines that had occurred during the past two Games; it was unclear whether they ought to have been part of the Olympic Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Added to the program were the javelin throw and the pentathlon.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The 1906 Games is noted for its opening and closing ceremonies, which initiated this tradition.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The 1908 Games introduced the tradition of the host coming in as the last in the parade also.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] These were the first Games to include an opening ceremony with athletes marching into the stadium as national teams behind their flags.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] King George I officially opened the Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Six thousand schoolchildren took part in the first ever Olympic closing ceremony.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] 854 athletes, 848 men and six women, from 20 countries, competed at the 1906 Intercalated Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] 78 events in 14 disciplines, comprising 12 sports, were part of the 1906 Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] These medals were distributed but are no longer recognized by the International Olympic Committee.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The **1908 Summer Olympics** (officially the **Games of the IV Olympiad** and also known as **London 1908**) were an international multi-sport event held in London, England, from 27 April to 31 October 1908.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The 1908 Games were relocated to London after Italy withdrew from hosting on financial grounds.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Archival research has established that the British Olympic Association was already privately exploring the possibility of London hosting the Games as early as 5 January 1906, three months before the eruption began.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] London was formally confirmed as host on 19 November 1906.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Rome eventually hosted the Games in 1960.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] These were the fourth chronological modern Summer Olympics in keeping with the now-accepted four-year cycle as opposed to the alternate four-year cycle of the proposed Intercalated Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The IOC president for these Games was Baron Pierre de Coubertin.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Lasting a total of 187 days (six months and four days), these were the longest Games in modern Olympics history.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] There were four bids for the 1908 Summer Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Rome was selected ahead of London, Berlin and Milan.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The selection was made at the 6th IOC Session in London in 1904.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Italian authorities were preparing to stage the games when Mount Vesuvius erupted on 7 April 1906, devastating the city of Naples.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Funds were diverted to the reconstruction of Naples, so a new host country was required.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] During the Intercalated Games of Athens, still in April 1906, Coubertin approached Lord Desborough about alternatively hosting in London.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Accepting the offer and with a mere 18 months in which to prepare, London was selected for the first time to hold the Games, which were held at White City alongside the Franco-British Exhibition, at the time the more noteworthy event.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The White City Stadium, built in short time for the Games, held 68,000 people, with full crowds turning up to watch the events.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The stadium track was three laps to the mile (536.448 metres per lap), as the current standard of 400 metres did not exist until 1962, with a pool (for swimming and diving events) and platforms (for wrestling and gymnastics) in the centre field.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] On the opening day, following the practice introduced at the Intercalated Games of 1906, teams paraded behind national flags.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The 1908 Olympics also prompted establishment of standard rules for sports, and selection of judges from different countries rather than just the host.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] One reason was the 400 metre race, in which a US runner, John Carpenter, was accused by the British officials of interfering with a British runner.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Part of the problem was the different definition of interference under British and international rules (the events were held under British rules by the decision of the Organising Committee).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The officials decided to disqualify Carpenter and ordered a second final race without him.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] British Halswelle was to face the other two finalists.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] These athletes, William Robbins and John Taylor, were both Americans and decided not to participate in the repeat of the final to protest against the judges' decision.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Halswelle was thus the only medallist in the 400 metres.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The most famous incident of the games came at the end of the marathon.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Dorando Pietri, Italy, began his race at a rather slow pace, but in the second half of the course began a powerful surge moving him into second position by the 32 km (20 mi) mark, 4 minutes behind South African Charles Hefferon.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] When he knew that Hefferon was in crisis, Pietri further increased his pace, overtaking him at the 39 km (24 mi) mark.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The effort took its toll and with only two kilometres to go, Pietri began to feel the effects of extreme fatigue and dehydration.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] When he entered the stadium, he took the wrong path and when umpires redirected him, he fell down for the first time.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] He got up with their help, in front of 75,000 spectators.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] He fell four more times, and each time the umpires helped him up.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] In the end, though totally exhausted, he managed to finish the race in first place.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Of his total time of 2h 54min 46s, ten minutes were needed for that last 340 metres.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The American team immediately lodged a complaint against the help Pietri received from the umpires.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The complaint was accepted and Pietri was disqualified and removed from the final standings of the race.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Since he had not been responsible for his disqualification, Queen Alexandra awarded him a gilded silver cup the next day.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] These Games were the first to include winter events, as had originally been proposed for the Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] There were four figure skating events, although held on 28 and 29 October, months after most of the other events.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Oscar Swahn from Sweden, who won the gold medal for running deer shooting, became the oldest Olympic champion of all time, and set another age record by being 72 years and 279 days old during his triumph at the 1920 Summer Olympics in Antwerp, Belgium.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] One of the more unusual shooting events in 1908 was Olympic dueling.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The discipline, which was an associate event (that is, not official), was performed by facing opponents wearing protective clothing and masks and firing wax bullets.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] American John Taylor was a member of the winning medley relay team, making him the first African-American athlete to win an Olympic gold medal.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Times for the winning team were United States (3:29.4): William Hamilton, 200 metres (22.0); Nathaniel Cartmell, 200 metres (22.2); John Taylor, 400 metres (49.8); and Melvin Sheppard, 800 metres (1:55.4).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Less than five months after returning from the Olympic Games in London, Taylor died of typhoid fever on 2 December 1908 at the age of 26.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The budget of the organising committee showed a cost of £15,000; over one-third was labelled "entertainment expense".
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Donations were the major source of revenue; only 28% of income derived from ticket sales.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Total receipts of £21,378 resulted in organisers claiming a profit.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Construction of the White City Stadium, which cost the government about £60,000, was not counted.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Twenty-two sports, representing 110 events in 25 sporting disciplines, were competed.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] A golf tournament had also been planned but it was cancelled a few days before it was scheduled to start.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Swimming, diving, and water polo are considered three disciplines of the same sport, *aquatics*.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] At the time, tug-of-war was part of athletics and the two different football codes (association and rugby (union)) were listed together.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee now considers tug-of-war a separate sport as well as referring to association football as simply "football" and to rugby union as "rugby." In one of seven cycling events (cycling sprint) no medals were awarded.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The sailing program was open for a total of five sailing classes, but actually only four sailing events were competed.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Cycle polo, glima and pistol dueling were demonstration sports.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Thirteen sports venues were used for the 1908 Summer Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The first winter sports took place at Prince's Skating Club in Knightsbridge.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] White City Stadium served as a precursor to modern stadiums.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The figure skating events were not held at the next Olympics in Stockholm, but returned for the 1920 Games in Antwerp, heralding the first Winter Olympics that took place in Chamonix in 1924.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] White City was the main venue for the 1934 British Empire Games (known as the Commonwealth Games since 1978) and, before its demolition in 1985, also served as a venue for the 1966 FIFA World Cup.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The All England Lawn Tennis Club continues to host the Wimbledon championships and is the only venue of the 1908 Games that was used for the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Bisley and Henley served as venues in the 1948 Games when the Olympics returned to London forty years later.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The 1908 Games featured athletes representing 22 National Olympic Committees.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Finland, Turkey and New Zealand (as part of the team from Australasia) made their first appearance at the Olympic Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The fact that the United Kingdom competed as a single team was upsetting to some Irish competitors, who felt that Ireland should compete on its own, despite being part of the UK at the time.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] They relied on the precedent set by Grand Duchy of Finland, which while being a part of the Russian Empire, competed in London as a separate country.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Fearing an Irish boycott, the authorities changed the name of the team to Great Britain/Ireland, and in two sports, field hockey and polo, Ireland participated as a separate country, winning silver medals in both, although their medals counted towards the UK's tally.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Irish athletes in the United States were not affected by this controversy, and many Irish immigrants to the United States competed for the U.S.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Olympic team as members of the Irish American Athletic Club.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Members of the Irish American Athletic Club won ten of the U.S.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Olympic team's total 23 gold medals, or as many as the nations of France, Germany and Italy combined.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Britain had more than a quarter of competitors in their team, with 676, compared to 112 on the American team which placed second in the medal standings.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1908 Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The **1912 Summer Olympics** (Swedish: *Olympiska sommarspelen 1912*), officially known as the **Games of the V Olympiad** (Swedish: *Den V olympiadens spel*) and commonly known as **Stockholm 1912**, were an international multi-sport event held in Stockholm, Sweden, between 6 July and 22 July 1912.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony was held on 6 July.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] They were the only Summer Olympics to be held in the 1910s as the 1916 Summer Olympics in Berlin were cancelled due to World War I.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Twenty-eight nations and 2,408 competitors, including 48 women, competed in 102 events in 14 sports.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] With the exception of tennis (starting on 5 May) and football and shooting (both starting on 29 June), the games were held within a month with an official opening on 6 July.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] It was the last Olympics to issue solid gold medals and, with Japan's debut, the first time an official team from an Asian nation participated.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Stockholm was the only bid for the games, and was selected in 1909.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The games were the first to have art competitions, women's diving, women's swimming, and the first to feature both the decathlon and the new pentathlon, both won by the American Jim Thorpe.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Electric timing was introduced in athletics, while the host country disallowed boxing.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Figure skating was rejected by the organizers because they wanted to promote the Nordic Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold medals (26), while hosts Sweden won the most medals overall (65).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] These were the final Olympic Games for eight years due to the disruption of the First World War.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The next Olympic Games were held in 1920 in Antwerp.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Following the 1908 Summer Olympics in London, authorities in Sweden immediately sought to ensure that the next games would be held there.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] There were two Swedish members of the International Olympic Committee (IOC) at the time, Viktor Balck and Clarence von Rosen.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The pair proposed the idea to the Swedish governing bodies of athletics and gymnastics in order to ensure that they backed any potential bid.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Support was given by the national associations on 18 April 1909 for a bid to host the Olympics in Stockholm on the basis that suitable financial arrangements could be made.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] King Gustaf V was petitioned on 6 May 1909 following the publication of preliminary plans for the Stockholm bid that the expected cost of hosting the Games would be 415,000 kronor (£23,050 or $115,250).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Government accepted the petition on behalf of the King and supported the bid.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] On 28 May, at the meeting of the IOC in Berlin, the Swedish representatives declared that they had full financial support for hosting the next Games in Stockholm.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] A deal was made with the German IOC representative on the basis that Berlin would host the 1916 Summer Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Pierre de Coubertin spoke at the meeting about his concerns that Sweden should ensure that the Games take place, as he did not want a repeat of the problems with Great Britain hosting the 1908 Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The news that Stockholm was to host the 1912 Olympics was received with enthusiasm by the Swedish public.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The organizing committee took de Coubertin's words to heart, and aimed to achieve an Olympic Games which removed those elements which detracted from earlier Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The committee was elected in the autumn of 1909, with Balck voted as the President of the committee, and Crown Prince Gustaf Adolf selected as Honorary President.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The committee's first meeting took place on 7 October, and on 11 October they delegated the arrangements for the individual branches of sports to the relevant governing bodies in Sweden.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] There were four exceptions to this, with the game shooting, modern pentathlon and mountain ascents retained by the Olympic committee, and the horse riding competitions being organized by Prince Carl, Duke of Västergötland, who was the inspector of the Swedish cavalry.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Altogether there were 187 members of these committees.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The official invitation to compete in the Games was issued on 18 November 1910 to 27 countries, either directly or through their representative on the IOC.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] A further 15 countries were to have been invited, but as they had no IOC representatives, the Swedish authorities were unsure how to proceed.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Once the organizing committee for the Games received confirmation of the athletic associations in each of the 15 countries, they too were sent invitations.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Some 61,800 entry forms were printed for the use of the various nations.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Free transport was arranged for the invited nations' equipment, and a discount of 50 percent was arranged for competitors and delegates on the state run railway.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] A daily newspaper which only covered the Olympics was arranged to be published during the Games, in both English and Swedish.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Further arrangements were made for the general arrival of visitors in order to entertain them whilst they were not at the Games; a pleasure garden was opened north of the Olympic Stadium, and a series of indoor tennis courts were converted into a restaurant.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Twelve sports venues were used in the 1912 Summer Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] This marked the first time that more than one venue would be used for the football tournament, which has been the case ever since.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Stockholm Olympic Stadium served as one of the equestrian venues for the 1956 Summer Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Råsunda Stadium served as a venue for the 1958 FIFA World Cup and the 1995 FIFA Women's World Cup.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] In the initial bid document it was identified that a new stadium would be needed, initially envisaged as being located in the Östermalm Athletic Grounds.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] In order to save funds, it was expected that only one of the stadium's stands would be permanent, with the other three made of wood and dismantled following the Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The cost of that stadium was estimated at 235,000 Kronor.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Arrangements were made with the individual national committees to provide the use of Östermalm Athletic Grounds and Traneberg.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The cycling road race was held around Mälaren, the third largest lake in Sweden.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The water events, including the swimming and the rowing, were held at Djurgårdsbrunnsviken, where a stadium was built.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Kaknäs was already used as a shooting range, but alterations were needed to accommodate shooting events.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Although it was not used as the Olympic stadium as originally intended, Östermalm hosted the lawn tennis and fencing competitions after a tennis pavilion was moved there from another location.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Five other locations were considered in addition to the Östermalm Athletic Grounds to locate the Olympic Stadium.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Stockholm Olympic Stadium was built on the site of the former Stockholm Athletic Grounds in order to retain the other locations for other uses during the Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] By placing it to the north of the city, the Olympic Stadium was within the immediate vicinity of other pre-existing sporting venues.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Initial funding was given to the sum of 400,000 Kr for a timber stadium but Torben Grut, the architect, also drew up alternative plans for a stone stadium.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] However it was found that the original estimate for the stone stadium would still be too expensive, and the plans were once more modified in order to simplify the design and reduce costs.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] An agreement was entered into with a contractor on 2 November 1910 that it would be transferred complete by 25 May 1912.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Games of the V Olympiad were opened on 6 July 1912.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish Royal Family left Stockholm Palace at 10:40am, and were received at the Olympic Stadium by members of the IOC.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Three thousand competing athletes had already assembled in the nearby Östermalm Athletic Grounds, and began to enter the stadium in alphabetical order by nation according to the Swedish spelling.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish team entered last, but unlike the later tradition, the Greek team did not enter first.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] A hymn was sung, a traditional Swedish chant was conducted and prayers were read first in Swedish and then in English.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Crown Prince Gustaf Adolf addressed the King on behalf of the Swedish Olympic Association.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Afterwards a trumpet fanfare was played and the Crown Prince called for cheers for the King.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The athletes in their national groups marching out of the stadium in order ended the ceremony.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish delegation at the IOC meeting in Berlin on 28 May 1909 had proposed a simple Olympic schedule containing only "pure" athletics, swimming, gymnastics and wrestling.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] However other countries requested that the schedule be more comprehensive, and with that in mind they put forward a further programme at the IOC meeting in 1911 which was met with approval.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The sports which were added were the tug of war, cycling, fencing, football, horse riding, lawn tennis, rowing, shooting, skating and yacht racing.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The question of adding skating to the programme was discussed once more on 7 February 1910, with the decision being made to drop it from the schedule.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] It was felt to be unsuitable because it was a winter sport, and it was to be part of the Nordic Games the following year.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Boxing was removed from the programme as it was unappealing to the Swedes.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Art competitions were considered at a further meeting on 14 February 1910, and were subsequently added to the programme, but now art competitions are no longer regarded as official Olympic events by the International Olympic Committee.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] As a result, now the 1912 Summer Olympics programme considered composed of 14 sports encompassing 18 disciplines and 102 events.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Baseball, Glima (as the second Olympic demonstration of the sport after 1908 Summer Olympics) and Gotland sports were unofficial demonstration sports.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] This was also the first year art competitions were held at the Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The athletic events saw the introduction of a fully automatic timing system developed by R.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] It involved attaching electromagnets to chronometers in a system which attached a control lamp to the starting gun for each race.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] This resulted in the firing of the gun starting a timer which was then stopped by one of the judges at the finishing line.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The final of the men's 100 metres was expected to be a mostly American affair, and it ended up with six athletes, only one of whom was not from the United States.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] It suffered from seven false starts before the athletes finally got away, with Ralph Craig winning the gold medal by 60 centimetres (24 in) in front of second place Alvah Meyer.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Donald Lippincott won bronze, 15 cm behind the second man.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Shizo Kanakuri, a Japanese marathon runner, went missing during the race.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] He lost consciousness by heatstroke and a farming family helped him to stop at a party taking place in a villa on the marathon route in order to quench his thirst, then caught a train to Stockholm and left the country the next day.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] He returned to Japan without notifying race officials.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Fifty years later, after being invited back by the Swedish authorities, he completed the race with an (unofficial) time of 54 years, 8 months, 6 days, 8 hours, 32 minutes and 20.3 seconds.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Portuguese Francisco Lázaro died from heat exhaustion while running the marathon, the only athlete to die during the running of an Olympic marathon.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] In addition to the physical toll of the event, the reported split time for the 5 km checkpoint at Stocksund (2:17:20 after a 1:48:00 start) implies an unusually slow 29:20 opening segment, followed by an unrealistically fast 10 km pace.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Martin has noted this discrepancy as a likely timing error.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] American Jim Thorpe won the pentathlon and the newly created decathlon.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Thorpe's gold medals were stripped by the International Olympic Committee in 1913, after the IOC learned that Thorpe had taken expense money for playing baseball, violating contemporary Olympic amateurism rules, before the 1912 Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] This moved everyone else up in the rankings.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] In 1982, the IOC was convinced that the disqualification had been improper, as no protest against Thorpe's eligibility had been brought within the required 30 days, and reinstated Thorpe's medals.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The replicas were presented to his children in 1983, 30 years after Thorpe's death.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Finally, in 2022, the IOC posthumously declared Thorpe as the sole winner of the pentathlon and decathlon events after extensive consultations with his former competitors' families who said they had always viewed Thorpe as the winner.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] New Olympic records were set in the majority of track and field events, with only the men's 200 metres, 10 km walk, standing high jump, standing broad jump, hop, step and jump, and the hurdle competitions failing to have new records set.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Tell Berna captured a gold for the 3000m and Henry S.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] "Harry" Babcock took gold for the pole vault, setting an Olympic Record at 3.95m.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Hannes Kolehmainen was the most successful in setting records at the games, with new Olympic Records set in the 5,000, 10,000 metre and cross country races.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The cycling events at the 1912 Games were limited to a road race around Lake Mälaren, which had already been a successful route for a yearly cycling race.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Although not originally in the schedule, several countries requested that track cycling be added; however, the organizing committee stuck by their plans not to build a new track cycling stadium as the only one in Stockholm had been destroyed in order for the Olympic Stadium to be built.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] In addition, Germany had specifically requested Cycle-Polo and Figure-Cycling to be added to the programme, both of which requests were turned down by the committee.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] It was decided to hold the road race as a time trial, and to outlaw any non-competitive cyclists acting as pacemakers.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Nineteen nations entered 151 athletes into the competition, which was a greater number than expected by the committee.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The largest group was from Great Britain, who had entered twelve competitors from England, another twelve from Scotland, and a further nine from Ireland.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The race began on 7 July, with the athletes leaving in groups.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The first group left at 2am, with the remaining groups leaving at intervals of two minutes.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The distance raced was 318 kilometres (198 mi), with South African Rudolph Lewis winning the gold medal in the individual race.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Frederick Grubb of Great Britain won the silver medal, and Carl Schutte of the United States won the bronze.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] However, the average positions of the Swedish team were better than their competitors', and so the Swedish team won the gold medal for the team competition.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The silver and bronze medals followed the individual victories, going to Great Britain and the United States respectively – giving Grubb and Schutte a second medal each of the same varieties.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] All of the medals in the men's competitions were split between the diving teams of the Sweden and Germany.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The men's high dive was a Swedish white out, with Swedish divers taking all three medal positions.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Erik Adlerz took the gold medal, and proceeded to take the gold medal for Sweden in the 10 metre platform too.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Albert Zürner took the silver for Germany, and Gustaf Blomgren won the bronze medal for Sweden.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Another white out occurred in the 3 metre springboard with all three medals going to the German team, with Paul Günther taking gold, Hans Luber in the silver medal position and Kurt Behrens in bronze.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] A 10-metre platform event also took place for women, with Sweden taking two more medals, Greta Johansson in gold and Lisa Regnell in silver.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Great Britain's Isabelle White won the bronze medal.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The remaining finalists were all from Sweden.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Equestrian made its first appearance at a modern Olympics in the 1912 Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Although competitions involving horse riding had been included in the programme of 1900, this was the first appearance of modern Olympic staples such as dressage, eventing and show jumping.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] It was expected that the competitors would be military personnel as they would have had the cavalry experience to compete.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The competition was split between the military competitions, prize riding and prize jumping.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] In the military competition, seven countries put forward competitors for the individual and team eventing.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Each nation put forward four athletes with the exception of Denmark, which only put forward three.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Some of the countries also nominated reserves in addition to their main athletes.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The total length of the course was 55 kilometres (34 mi) with the start and finish both in the grounds of the Field Riding Club.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The heat was such on the day of the event that competitors lost as much as 4.5 pounds (2.0 kg) in weight.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Swede Axel Nordlander won the individual competition, and led the Swedish eventing team to victory as well, earning himself two gold medals.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] In second place in the individual competition was German Friedrich von Rochow, who also earned a second silver medal as the team from Germany placed second overall.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Only the bronze medals were split up between nationalities, with the American team including Guy Vernor Henry, Jr. taking the bronze for the team event, while Frenchman Jacques Cariou won the individual medal.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Two additional countries entered for the dressage, although only Sweden entered the maximum number of competitors.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The event resulted in Sweden taking all three medals, with the gold going to Carl Bonde, the silver to Gustaf Adolf Boltenstern and the bronze to Hans von Blixen-Finecke.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The team event saw Sweden take another gold medal, with the French team second and the German team, featuring Prince Friedrich Karl of Prussia, in the bronze medal position.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The foil competition became a full Olympic event, having appeared at the 1908 Games as a demonstration sport.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Nedo Nadi and Pietro Speciale of Italy took the gold and silver medals respectively, and Richard Verderber of Austria placed third.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] There were individual and team events in both épée and sabre.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The épée team event saw Belgium take the gold medal and Great Britain and the Netherlands in second and third place respectively.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] A member of the Belgian team went on to take the individual title as well, with Paul Anspach taking the gold medal.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Ivan Joseph Martin Osiier of Denmark took the silver medal, and another Belgian who was not in the team event, Philippe le Hardy de Beaulieu, won the bronze medal.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The sabre competition was dominated by the competitors from Hungary, with their team taking the gold medal over Austria and the Netherlands.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The individual competition saw a shut out by Hungarian athletes with Jenő Fuchs winning the overall competition, Béla Békessy in second and Ervin Mészáros in third.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Thirteen countries signalled their intention to enter football teams for the 1912 Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] A standard cup tie system was implemented, with the final deciding the gold and silver medallists and a third/fourth position playoff deciding the bronze medal winner.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Only FIFA affiliated teams were allowed to take part, with the public draw for the tournament taking place on 18 June 1911.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The tournament itself started on 29 June.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] In the first round Finland defeated Italy 3–2, Austria beat Germany 5–1 and the Netherlands emerged victorious over Sweden 4–3.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The team from Great Britain, who had won the gold medal at the 1908 Summer Games, were given a bye to the second round, where they faced Hungary and won 7–0.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Finland also won their match, defeating Russia 2–1.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Denmark matched the British scoreline, winning 7–0 against Norway, and the Netherlands won against Austria 3–1.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The semi final matches pitted Great Britain against Finland, where they won 4–0, and Denmark against the Netherlands, ending in a 4–1 victory for Denmark.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Netherlands won the third/fourth place playoff by the biggest scoreline of the tournament, beating Finland 9–0.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Later on the same day the final was played in the Olympic Stadium, where Great Britain retained its gold medal against Denmark in front of 25,000 spectators.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Goals from Harold Walden, Arthur Berry and two from Gordon Hoare helped Britain to win by a margin of 4–2.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The gymnastic competition at the 1912 Games featured a single individual competition and three team events in addition to a variety of displays by the various teams.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish team naturally won the Gymnastics event of the Swedish system, referred to in the programme as "Team Competition I", with fellow Scandinavian teams Denmark and Norway taking the second and third positions.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The all around team competition came second, with Italy taking the gold.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] In addition, one of the Italian team members, Alberto Braglia, won the individual gold for the same event.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Louis Ségura of the French team won the individual silver, while another member of the Italian team, Adolfo Tunesi, won the individual bronze.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The all around team competition saw Hungary take the silver medal and the team from Great Britain in third place.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The final team competition allowed for a free choice of movements and apparatus.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] This was another all Scandinavian affair, with the Norwegian team emerging victorious, Finland in second and Denmark in the bronze medal position.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Modern pentathlon was competed for at the 1912 Games, marking its first appearance in the Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] It was for these games that the five events of shooting, swimming, equestrian, fencing and cross country running were decided to make up the pentathlon.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The competition was spread out across five days from 7 through to 12 July, ending with the cross country race.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Only men participated in the event, although a woman named Helen Preece was briefly enrolled to compete until the organizing committee ultimately denied her entry.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] For the shooting element, each competitor was allowed to bring their own pistol.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The shooting part of the competition was won by Gösta Åsbrink, with Georg de Laval and Gösta Lilliehöök in second and third place respectively, all three representing Sweden.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The swimming event was three lengths, each of 100 metres (330 ft), with the athletes split into eight heats and times going forward to calculate positions.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Ralph Clilverd of Great Britain won this event, with Edmond Bernhardt of Austria in second and de Laval in third.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The fencing competition saw each competitor face off against each other.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Several opponents were noted for their particular skill in the event with Åke Grönhagen of Sweden coming first with 24 wins, Jean de Mas Latrie of France second with 23, Sidney Stranne of Sweden in third with 21 and Patton of the United States close behind with 20.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Thirteen of the competitors cleared the equestrian course without any penalties, with Grönhagen winning the event, Bror Mannström of Sweden in second and de Laval third.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The cross country run was over 4,000 metres and started in the Olympic Stadium itself.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The event was run as a time trial with competitors leaving one minute apart.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] As this was the final event, the winning competitors were announced after the race, with Lilliehöök winning the gold medal, Åsbrink taking silver and de Laval, bronze.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The highest placed non-Swedish competitor was Patton, who finished fifth.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The rowing events at the 1912 Olympics did not prove popular with the public.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] This was put down to the "fatigue" of the public due to the volume of sporting events.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The eight competition was split into heats, with two teams in each heat.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The two British crews were lucky not to be drawn against each other, with the team from Leander Club facing New College, Oxford in the final.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Leander won by a length with a time of 6:15.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The coxed four followed a similar format to the eights, with the German team from Ludwigshafener Ruderverein defeating Britain's Thames Rowing Club in the final.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The competition for the coxed four, inriggers was much smaller, with only four nations competing.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Danish team defeated Sweden in the final.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The single sculls heats proved controversial with the first round race between Mart Kuusik and Alfred Heinrich being re-run after a protest by Heinrich.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] In addition, Cecil McVilly was disqualified in the first round after colliding with the boat of Martin Stahnke.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Wally Kinnear of Great Britain defeated Polydore Veirman of Belgium in the final, with Kinnear winning the matchup easily.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The yachts for the sailing competition assembled at Nynäshamn on 19 July, along with the other vessels that were to take part in an Olympic regatta.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The racing itself started the following day with the 12 metre class.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] There were only three nations and yachts competing in this event, the hosts Sweden, as well as Norway and Finland.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Norway won the gold medal, Sweden the silver and Finland came in last place, winning bronze.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The 10 metre class had the same number of countries entering it, although this time Sweden entered two yachts and Russia competed instead of Norway.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish yacht *Kitty* was the winning vessel, with the Finnish boat in second and the Russians coming third.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] A slightly improved field was featured in the 8 metre class, with four countries entering two yachts each.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The medals were awarded to exactly the same nations as the 12 metre class, another all Scandinavian affair.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The 6 metre class saw the most diverse field of any of the sailing events at the 1912 Olympics: six countries entered a total of nine yachts.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] France and Denmark competed in their only sailing event, along with Sweden, sending two yachts each.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Those three nations were the successful in the event, with the French yacht *Mac Miche* taking the gold, the Danish *Nurdug II* taking silver and the Swedish *Kerstin* placing third.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] There were eighteen shooting events at the 1912 Olympics, of which eight were team events.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The competition was split predominantly into three sections: military rifle shooting, shooting with miniature rifles, pistols and revolvers, and clay bird and running deer shooting.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Swedish and American competitors were the most successful at the competition, with seven gold medals each, although Sweden won a total of seventeen medals while the United States team won fourteen.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] 64-year-old Oscar Swahn, part of the Swedish single shot running deer team, is still the oldest gold medal winner in Olympic history.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] In swimming, Hawaiian Duke Kahanamoku won the 100 metre freestyle for the United States, who also saw Harry Hebner win gold in the 100 metre backstroke.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Canadian team also took two gold medals, both by George Hodgson in the 400 and 1,500 metre events.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The German swimming team won all three medals in the 200 metre breaststroke, with the gold going to Walter Bathe, who won a further gold in the 400 metre breaststroke.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Australasian team was victorious in the men's relay, with the United States finishing in the silver medal position and Great Britain placing third.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The 1912 Games saw the implementation of swimming events for women, with the 100 metre freestyle and 400 metre team relay taking place.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Fanny Durack won the individual contest, breaking the world record for the distance in the fourth heat.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Her fellow Australian Mina Wylie won the silver medal, and Jennie Fletcher of Great Britain came third to take the bronze medal.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The British team had further success in the women's relay, winning the team relay with the German team in second place and the Austrian team in third.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Because only four countries entered the relay there were no heats; only a final was held.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The United States did not field a women's team.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] New Olympic Records were set in all swimming events at the 1912 Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Tennis on covered courts was agreed initially for the 1912 Games, with competitions run for gentlemen's singles and doubles, ladies' singles, and mixed doubles.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The outdoor tournament was confirmed once the Östermalm Athletic Grounds were completed in late 1911, with the plans modified to have both indoor and outdoor tournaments.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Six countries sent players for the covered court competitions, with representatives from Sweden, Great Britain, Denmark, France, Australasia, and Bohemia appearing.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Included in this lineup was Australasia's only competitor, Anthony Wilding from New Zealand, who was also the reigning Wimbledon gentlemen's champion.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The indoor knockout competition started on 5 May, and continued as expected until the semi-final round where Wilding was beaten by Britain's Charles P.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The British player met Frenchman André Gobert in the final, but Gobert was victorious over the Englishman in straight sets.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Wilding took the bronze medal in a playoff against another British player, Arthur Lowe.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The outdoors tennis competition saw 70 players enter from 12 nations.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] However, Great Britain did not enter any competitors as the dates of the outdoor competition clashed with the 1912 Wimbledon Championships, despite attempts by the British authorities to convince the Olympic organizing committee to change the dates.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Other noted tennis players refused to compete at the Olympics and instead attended Wimbledon.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The gold and silver medals in the gentlemen's singles ended up being decided between two South Africans, with Charles Winslow and Harold Kitson playing each other.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The duo also competed as a pair in the gentlemen's doubles and took the gold medal, beating the Austrians Felix Pipes and Arthur Zborzil.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Marguerite Broquedis of France defeated Dorothea Koring of Germany in the ladies' singles for the gold medal.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] In the mixed doubles Koring teamed up with Heinrich Schomburgk to win the gold, the duo defeating Sigrid Fick and Gunnar Setterwall of Sweden in the final.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The tug of war competition was scheduled to take place between 7 and 12 July, with two matches taking place each day.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] However, out of the five countries which elected to enter the competition, only two actually appeared.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Great Britain arrived for its match against Bohemia, but the opposition team was nowhere to be found.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The same thing happened once more for the second match, with the Swedish team, made up of policemen from Stockholm, arriving to find that the Austrian team had not arrived.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Sweden was announced as the winners of the match in the Austrians' absence.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] On the second day of the competition, Great Britain took on Sweden, the only occasion where both teams actually turned up for the bout.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The British team were made up of the winners of the gold medal in the same event at the 1908 Games, with the exception of John Sewell and Mathias Hynes.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] As the British team also consisted of policemen, the bout ended up effectively being between the City of London Police and the Stockholm Police, with the Swedish team winning 2–0.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Due to the non-appearance of the team from Luxembourg, that one match ended up being the entire tug of war event at the 1912 Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Sweden was awarded the gold medal and Great Britain the silver.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The water polo tournament was set up on a modified elimination system as there were six teams entered.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The first round saw the British team defeating the Belgian team, Sweden defeating the French team and Austria defeating Hungary.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Lots were drawn to determine which match would take place in the second round as there were three teams left in the competition.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Great Britain were drawn to face Sweden, who they defeated.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Austria automatically qualified for the final against the winner of the Britain-Sweden matchup.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Great Britain won the gold medal in the event, defeating Austria 8–0.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Playoff matches were then played between each pair of defeated teams in order to decide the second and third places.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Sweden and Belgium played off after a further three matches to decide the silver and bronze medal positions, with Sweden emerging victorious 4–2.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The nations at the 1912 Games entered a total of 267 wrestlers, although the actual competitors who appeared in Sweden were fewer, with 171 actually turning up to compete.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Greco-Roman wrestling was the only style of wrestling competed for at the Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The bouts took place in the open air in an area of the Olympic stadium, with the wrestlers split according to weight into five divisions: featherweight, lightweight, middleweight A (later referred to as middleweight), middleweight B (later referred to as light heavyweight) and heavyweight.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The skills of the competitors from Finland were noted in the featherweight competition, with Kaarlo Koskelo taking the gold medal, while German Georg Gerstäcker took silver and a further medal went to Finland with Otto Lasanen taking bronze.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The lightweight class drew the most attention from the public, with Emil Väre winning gold after beating all of his opponents by pin rather than by points.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Swedish wrestlers Gustaf Malmström and Edvin Mattiasson took the silver and bronze medals respectively.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Claes Johanson won Sweden's only gold medal in the middleweight competition, with his fellow finalist from Russia, Martin Klein, retiring before fighting Johanson in the final.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] This was due to the semi-final match between Klein and Alfred Asikainen of Finland lasting 11 hours and forty minutes, although they took breaks for refreshments every half-hour.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Klein was awarded the silver medal and Asikainen the bronze.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The light heavyweight competition saw another marathon length match, with the bout between Anders Ahlgren of Sweden and Ivar Böhling of Finland for the gold medal lasting more than nine hours.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The match was then declared a draw with both athletes being awarded the silver medal as neither won the match.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The bronze medal went to Hungary's Béla Varga, who was defeated by Ahlgren in the semi-final match.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Yrjö Saarela of Finland was victorious in the heavyweight competition after having placed second in the light heavyweight event at the 1908 Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Johan Olin took another medal for Finland with the silver and Søren Marinus Jensen repeated his bronze medal at the 1908 Olympics with another for Denmark.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The 1912 Summer Olympics saw the introduction of art competitions at the Summer Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Events were implemented for literature, sculpture, painting, architecture and music.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Walter Winans won the gold medal for his sculpture, *An American Trotter*, which added to his previous gold medal for the running deer (double shot) competition at the 1908 Olympics and the silver medal in the running deer competition in 1912.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Baron Pierre de Coubertin, President of the IOC and founder of the modern Olympic movement, won the gold medal for literature.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] He actually entered the competition under the pseudonyms of Georges Hohrod and Martin Eschbach from Germany.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] With the exception of the sculpture competition, only gold medals were issued.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Italian Riccardo Barthelemy won the medal for music with his *Olympic Triumphal March*, and fellow countryman Giovanni Pellegrini won the gold for painting.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Swiss architects Eugène-Edouard Monod and Alphonse Laverrière shared the gold for their stadium design.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The sole silver medal, for sculpture, went to Frenchman Georges Dubois for his *Model of the entrance to a modern stadium*.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] In the evening of 7 July, demonstrations took place in the Olympic Stadium of sports from the Swedish island of Gotland.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] These began at 7:30pm with a demonstration of Pärk, a type of tennis with seven players a side.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] At the same time, at the other end of the stadium, a type of Icelandic wrestling called Glima was demonstrated.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Once those displays had concluded, further demonstrations were made of the Swedish sport varpa, similar to quoits, and stångstörtning, a version of the caber toss.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The three disciplines showcased were pärk, varpa and stångstörtning.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Baseball was also demonstrated at the Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] A game was played between the United States, the nation where the game was developed, and Sweden, the host nation.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The game was held on Monday, 15 July 1912 and started at 10 a.m. on the Ostermalm Athletic Grounds in Stockholm.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The Americans were represented by various members of the American Olympic track and field athletics delegation, while the Swedish team was the Vesterås Baseball Club, which had been formed in 1910 as the first baseball club in Sweden.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Four of the Americans played for Sweden, as the Swedish pitchers and catchers were inexperienced.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] One Swede eventually relieved Adams and Nelson, the American pitchers.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Six innings were played, with the Americans not batting in the sixth and allowing the Swedes to have six outs in their half of the inning.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The game was umpired by George Wright, a retired American National League baseball player.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Twenty-eight nations competed at the 1912 Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Egypt participated for the first time, as did Luxembourg, Iceland, Portugal, and Serbia.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Japan also made their Olympic debut, marking the first appearance of an Asian country at an Olympic Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Chile made its first appearance as a national team, with fourteen athletes attending the Games, although it had previously entered one individual at the 1896 Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] This was also the first time that athletes from Armenia had competed in the Olympics, as part of the team from Turkey (the officially recognised name for the Ottoman Empire).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Serbia's appearance was the only time it attended an Olympic Games as an independent nation until the 2008 Summer Olympics, almost one hundred years later.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The only nation that participated in the previous games in London 1908 but was absent in Stockholm 1912 was Argentina.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The polity known as Austria-Hungary is mistakenly considered a single sovereign country, while in reality they were two sovereign states in real union with a single monarch who was titled both emperor of Austria and king of Hungary.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] At the time, Australasia (Australia and New Zealand), Canada and South Africa were all part of the British Empire.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Egypt was de jure under the control of Turkey, but had been de facto run by the British since 1882.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] This was the last Olympics that allowed "private entries", i.e. individual athletes that were not part of a country's officially selected team.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] Arnold Jackson was one such private entry; he won the 1500 metres by 0.1 seconds, ahead of an American trio, in what was acclaimed at the time to be "the greatest race ever run".
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] His medal is still credited to the United Kingdom, however.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] These are the top 10 nations that won medals at the 1912 Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1912-summer-olympics] The medals themselves included solid gold medals, the last time these were given out.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] The **1916 Summer Olympics** (German: *Olympische Sommerspiele 1916*), officially known as the **Games of the VI Olympiad** (German: *Spiele der VI.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] Olympiade*), were scheduled to be held in Berlin, Germany, but they were cancelled due to the outbreak of World War I, the first time in the twenty-year history of the Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] Berlin was selected as the host city during the 14th IOC Session in Stockholm on 4 July 1912, defeating bids from Alexandria, Amsterdam, Brussels, Budapest and Cleveland.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] After the 1916 Games were cancelled, Berlin would eventually host the 1936 Summer Olympics, twenty years later.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] Work on the stadium, the Deutsches Stadion ("German Stadium"), began in 1912 at what was the Grunewald Race Course.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] It was planned to seat more than 18,000 spectators.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] On 8 June 1913, the stadium was dedicated with the release of 10,000 pigeons.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] At the outbreak of World War I in 1914, organization continued as it was not expected that the war would continue for several years.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] Eventually, though, the Games were cancelled.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] A winter sports week with speed skating, figure skating, ice hockey and Nordic skiing was planned; the concept of this week eventually gave rise to the first Winter Olympic Games in 1924.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] The central venue was to have been the Deutsches Stadion.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] If the games had been played, Finland (as the Grand Duchy of Finland) would not have been allowed to take part as an independent delegation (as it had done previously) due to Russia revoking its autonomy of participating in international sport in 1914.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] Berlin returned to Olympic bidding in 1931, when it beat Barcelona, Spain, for the right to host the 1936 Summer Olympics, the last Olympics before the outbreak of World War II.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] At the beginning of 1914, there were fast preparations for the upcoming Olympic Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] First, they had to build the stadium, which took a very long time.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] After that, Carl Diem, General Secretary of the Organising Committee for the 1916 Games, had to focus on financing the games, which was difficult because the cost would come to about 1,321 million marks (US$738,902,671).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] Later on, the board of the Olympic Games got together to discuss the programs that were to be sent out to athletes and their families to prepare for the amount of attendees who were to arrive.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] Most of the IOC (International Olympic Committee) members did not know what year to schedule the Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] Some believed that the war would not last long and that the Olympics would be able to take place like everyone had planned.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] Diem, a German man, believed that the war would not last a long time.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] Even though he thought that, the IOC sent out invitations saying that the Olympics would be postponed until "a more peaceful time" (Kluge 13).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] In 1914, Pierre de Coubertin signed a contract between Herriot and Count Édouard d’Assche.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] In this contract, he "promised to postpone its plan until 1924, in the event that Antwerp maintained its candidature for 1920" (Kluge 15).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] His biggest concern was with the IOC which had made him president in 1907 for the span of ten years.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] He knew that he had a big responsibility and would not let go of his lead in this role.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] Coubertin, who played an important role in the decision of where these Olympics should take place, was proposed with many confrontations about moving the Olympics to years ahead, even in different countries.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] With much consideration, he had decided that the Olympics would stay in Berlin, but the year would change.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] Although this was a tough decision, knowing that there would not be a shortage of competitors was comforting.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] On 8 August 1915, the stadium was reopened to hold "war competitions" in swimming and cycling, but on 10 February 1916, the Competition Committee of the DRAfOS finally got together again, not since the beginning of the war.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] They had decided that there would be small games that would take place to get different athletes a chance to compete.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] Despite the efforts of Coubertin, Diem and many others, the official games had to be canceled and only resumed in 1920, after the end of the war.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1916-summer-olympics] The Summer Olympics ultimately took place in Berlin in 1936, twenty years after they were supposed to happen, and eighteen years after the war had ended.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The **1988 Winter Olympics**, officially known as the **XV Olympic Winter Games** (French: *XVes Jeux olympiques d'hiver*) and commonly known as **Calgary 1988** were a multi-sport event held from February 13 to 28, 1988, with Calgary, Alberta, as the main host city.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] This marks the most recent time that two consecutive Olympic Games were hosted in North America (with the 1984 Summer Olympic Games hosted in Los Angeles, California, United States).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It was the first Winter Olympic Games to be held for 15 days, like the counterpart Summer Olympic Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The majority of the events took place in Calgary itself.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] However, the snow events were shared by Nakiska ski resort in Kananaskis Country at the west of the city and the Canmore Nordic Centre Provincial Park in the town of Canmore.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It was the last Winter Olympics that took place during the Cold War.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In 1988, a record 57 National Olympic Committees (NOC) sent a total of 1,424 athletes to these Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] These Winter Olympics would be the last attended for both the Soviet Union and East Germany NOCs.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Just like the 1976 Summer Olympics, host country Canada failed again to win a gold medal on their home soil (they won three gold medals in demonstration events, but these are not included in the official medal table).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Finnish ski jumper, Matti Nykänen, and the Dutch speed skater, Yvonne van Gennip, won three individual gold medals each.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The 1988 Winter Olympics were also remembered for the "heroic failure" of both the British ski jumper, Michael Edwards, and the debut of the Jamaica national bobsleigh team.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Both of them became subjects of major feature films about their participation in these Games: *Cool Runnings* by Walt Disney Pictures in 1993 and *Eddie the Eagle* by 20th Century Fox in 2016.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] At approximately C$829 million, the Calgary Games were the most expensive Olympics ever held at the time, as all the necessary infrastructure was built from scratch.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The facilities that were built for these Winter Olympics helped the host region to turn into the heart of Canada's elite winter sports program, under the tutelage of WinSport.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] After the Games, their legacy still standing and in constant use, as the five purpose-built venues for those Games are now used for training and hosting various winter sporting events every year.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] These policies helped Canada develop into one of the top nations in Winter Olympics competition.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The climax of this effort was the overall first-place finish at the 2010 Winter Olympics in Vancouver, Canada.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Calgary made its fourth attempt at hosting the Winter Games when it bid for the 1988 Winter Olympic Games, which also marked Canada's seventh bid for the Winter Olympic Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Montreal made the first Canadian bid for the Winter Games in 1956 and won the rights to host the 1976 Summer Olympics, and Vancouver made attempts to host the 1976 and 1980 Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Calgary, alongside neighbouring Banff, under the leadership of the Calgary Olympic Development Association (CODA), submitted bids for the Winter Games in 1964, 1968, and 1972.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] However, CODA went dormant in 1966 after losing three consecutive bids.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In 1978, Frank King and Bob Niven of Calgary's Booster Club took over the organization's leadership and revived CODA.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] King and Niven consulted former Olympic Sprinter and CODA founder, Ernie McCullough, and politician Arthur Ryan Smith, who had worked on previous bids, for guidance on the project.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In October 1979, CODA secured the Canadian Olympic Association's (COA) support for Canada's official bid to host the 1988 Winter Olympics, winning over a competing bid by Vancouver with a vote of 27–9.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Calgary's bid was at the time the most ambitious for the Winter Olympics ever, as the city lacked winter sports facilities and almost everything would have to be built from scratch.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] CODA proposed constructing all new venues, arguing that if Calgary was awarded the Games, Canada's inventory of training facilities would increase significantly.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Vancouver bidding committee argued that Calgary's bid represented a "Big-ticket Games" idea, and estimated to cost nearly three times what Vancouver was expected to pay to host the Winter Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Vancouver's bid was based on already developed infrastructure, including the Expo 86 precinct, the Pacific Coliseum and Whistler Blackcomb, which later served as the basis for the successful 2010 Winter Olympics bid and the later unsuccessful 2030 Winter Olympics bid.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] CODA then spent two years building local support for the megaproject, selling CA$5 memberships to approximately 80,000 of Calgary's 600,000 residents.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Calgary also secured CA$270 million in funding from the federal (CA$200 million) and provincial governments.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Some civic leaders, including then-mayor Ralph Klein, travelled around the world to lobby IOC delegates.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The arrival of the National Hockey League's (NHL) newly relocated Calgary Flames from Atlanta in 1980 drove the city to construct a new multi-use arena that would later be named the Olympic Saddledome, demonstrating to the IOC Calgary's determination to host the Winter Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Olympic bid itself emphasized the unique cultural and natural characteristics who mark the Calgary Metropolitan Region and the Alberta Province and also canadian prairies landscapes, as a perfect places for hosting the Winter Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] At the bidding documents, the city was marketed with a capitalist, oil-driven and vibrant economy that also had mountain playgrounds, extensive wilderness, and a rodeo culture.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] When the two images of Calgary and Alberta were brought together, they seemed to be contrasting; however, they complemented each other as part of extensive and intense bidding lobby process.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Calgary was one of three finalists during the 1988 Winter Olympics bid process.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The other two were Falun, Sweden, and Cortina d'Ampezzo, Italy.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Italian town (comune) had before hosted the 1956 Winter Olympics and was seen by many as the favorite.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The vote was held on September 30, 1981, in Baden-Baden, West Germany, during the 84th IOC Session and 11th Olympic Congress.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] After Cortina d'Ampezzo was eliminated in the first round of balloting, Calgary won in the second and final round of balloting over Falun, by a margin of 17 votes.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The announcement of CODA's victory sent the delegates in Baden-Baden and Calgary residents into singing and dancing.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It also made then Alberta premier, Peter Lougheed, burst openly into tears in front of the cameras.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Later, Ralph Klein sang a rendition of Mac Davis' *It's Hard to Be Humble*.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It was the first Winter Olympics awarded to Canada and the second Olympic Games overall, following the 1976 Summer Olympics in Montreal.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Cortina d'Ampezzo, along with Milan, would get to host the 2026 Winter Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Pelle noted that once the Games were awarded to Calgary, the cultural and community aspects of the bid were pushed aside by the newly formed Calgary Olympic organizing committee called the *Olympiques Calgary Olympics '88* (OCO'88).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It then proceeded to take on a "vigorous, resilient, and impersonal corporate business strategy" based in the work made by Los Angeles 1984 Organizing Committee (LAOCOG) toward the planning and operation of the Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Bill Pratt was a former general contractor who took over as OCO'88 president in 1983.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] He was the main manager that oversaw the construction of the Olympic megaproject.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Donald Jacques, a former general manager of the Calgary Exhibition and Stampede, once said, "Because of him, everything was built on time and on budget." However, Bill Pratt was controversial by rubbing many of his colleagues the wrong way.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] One former co-worker once predicted back in 1983: "He will get everything built.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] There may not be many (of us) left around to enjoy it, but he'll get it done." His relations with the news media were also strained at times.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] He had barely settled into his new position when the Calgary press media began criticizing OCO'88 for excessive secrecy and for awarding Olympic contracts to Calgary's PR firm Francis Williams and Johnson Ltd.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Pratt was a director of that firm, before accepting the organizing committee job.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] OCO'88 had insisted that there was no conflict of interest involved in the whole process.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Therefore, Pratt declared: "I have been nailed for a lot, but that does not bother me.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] After the 1988 Winter Olympics bid was won in 1981, OCO'88 made a new technical assessment and had to re-plan all the originally proposed competition venues except for the few that already existed and were within the campus of the University of Calgary.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] McMahon Stadium, the primary outdoor facility used mainly by the Canadian Football League's (CFL) Calgary Stampeders and inside of the University of Calgary and had originally been chosen to host only the opening ceremonies and the Saddledome was chosen to be the place of the closing ceremonies.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] But with the constant revisions of the project, the later addition of 4 more days in competition and mainly the gigantic demands for tickets, the Organizing Committee decided to move the closing ceremony to the Stadium which held twice the capacity of the Saddledome.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The last time that the two Winter Olympic ceremonies were held at the same venue was at the 1960 Winter Olympics in Squaw Valley, California.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The 1988 Winter Olympics' five main all-purpose venues were created at a significant cost at that time.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Three of them are located within Calgary and the other two are located west of the city.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] First, the Olympic Saddledome was planned to be the main venue of the games, hosting ice hockey and figure skating finals.This arena is also part of Stampede Park and was expected to cost C$83 million, but a cost overrun pushed it to nearly C$100 million and caused a nine-month delay.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Second, the Olympic Oval was built on the campus of the University of Calgary for C$40 million.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Third, Canada Olympic Park (formerly called the *Paskapoo Ski Hill*) was renovated for C$200 million and is located on the western outskirts of Calgary.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] This most expensive venue of these Winter Olympics hosted the men's bobsleigh, luge, and men's ski jumping and its portion of the Nordic combined events.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Also, it hosted some events of the demonstration sport of freestyle skiing.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] From the west of Calgary, the other two main all-purpose venues were built at the foothills of the Rocky Mountains.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] First, the Canmore Nordic Centre was 90% funded by the province of Alberta, for C$17.3 million.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It is located beside the town of Canmore and it hosted cross-country skiing, plus its men's portion of the Nordic combined, and the men's biathlon events.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It was projected that the area could become a year-round destination for Albertans, by facilitating and accelerate Canmore's economic transition away from coal mining to tourist attraction.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] However, the Nakiska (*Cree* meaning "to meet") ski resort was the most controversial and polemic complex built for these Winter Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It is located on Mount Allan (inside Kananaskis Country) and it hosted the alpine skiing events.It cost around C$25 million to Alberta government funds.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] This venue drew a lot of criticisms because of the various environmental concerns, the rejection by International Ski Federation (FIS) of slopes for each of the 10 events in the program and the use of artificial snow due to the lack of natural snow on that season.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] After the first inspections, the International Ski Federation (FIS) officials noted the venue's lack of technical difficulties needed for the Olympic competition.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Therefore, these FIS delegates proposed some major changes in the slopes in an action to cause bigger difficulties.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] These modifications were met with praise from Olympic alpine skiing competitors.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Like at Canada Olympic Park, this venue also hosted some freestyle skiing events as a demonstration sport.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Three other existing facilities served as secondary competition venues for the Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The first one, was the Max Bell Centre hosted the demonstration sports of curling and short track speed skating.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Father David Bauer Olympic Arena and the Stampede Corral shared the functions of secondary venues for the ice hockey tournament and the figure skating preliminaries.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Though the Stampede Corral did not support the International Ice Hockey Federation's (IIHF) standard-sized Olympic ice surface, OCO'88 was able to convince the IIHF to sanction the ice rink for Olympic competition, in exchange for a C$1.2 million payment.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] A record 57 National Olympic Committees (NOCs) entered athletes at the 1988 Winter Olympics, with eight more NOCs than any other previous Olympic Winter Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] 1,109 men and 315 women, for a total of 1,424 athletes, participated in these Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Fiji, Guam, Guatemala, Jamaica, the Netherlands Antilles and the Virgin Islands had their Winter Olympics debut in 1988.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] There were 46 events contested in 6 sports (10 disciplines).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In addition, there were 22 events in 4 demonstration sports and disciplines that have no official status in the overall medal tally.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The weather conditions were a problem facing OCO'88 during the Games, with temperatures ranging from −28 to 22 °C (−18 to 72 °F).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] After an unexpectedly freezing opening ceremony, the outdoor competitions scheduled to start the next day had to be postponed.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] This ended up affecting the men's downhill skiing event at Nakiska which was postponed for one day, due to Chinook winds blowing up to 160 km/h.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The women's downhill event also experienced the same scenario.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] With the ski jumping venue facing north at Canada Olympic Park (COP), the same winds also disrupted those events, with the large hill event being postponed four times.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It also disrupted the Nordic combined events, in which the ski jumping part had to be postponed as well.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] This situation ended up causing something unprecedented in the history of the Winter Olympics, as for the first time both the ski jumping and Nordic combined cross-country skiing events were contested in a single day.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Despite using artificial cooling, the bobsleigh and luge events did not need to be rescheduled; however, several races had to be postponed because of the high temperatures recorded and also because of the dirt that was carried away by these winds.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Calgary Olympic Development Association (CODA) Board of Directors had originally 25 members.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It was chaired by Frank King, followed by former Mayors Ralph Klein and Ross Alger, and other prominent Calgarians.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The executive committee president was Robert Niven.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Olympic Organizing Committee (OOC) was formed by utilizing many of the original board of directors members.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It was initially started with 11 members and was grown to 25 members by October 1983.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It grew further to 29 members by 1985, when former Alberta premier, Peter Lougheed, was added to the list.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] An Olympic biographer, Kevin Wamsley, noted that the CEO Frank King, President Bill Pratt, Ralph Klein, and former COA President Roger Jackson had collectively the most influence on all aspects of these Winter Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] This organizing committee took a hierarchical form for planning these Olympics, which caused consternation from some staff, volunteers, and people in executive roles.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The original staff, who were at odds with the current management structure, were either fired or willingly resigned.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Also, there were claims that some of the volunteers were verbally abused.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] As a result, David Leighton resigned as OOC President in 1982, after only five months on the job.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Therefore, Bill Pratt, a former general manager of the Calgary Stampede, became the new OCOG's president shortly afterwards.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The City of Calgary and the Canadian Olympic Association (COA) delegated officially all Olympic responsibilities, including staging the Winter Olympics under the Olympic Charter, to the newly formed OCO'88 in February and September 1983 respectively.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] However, conflicts within OCO'88 grew in the public eye and a review of the entire management structure was conducted after Ralph Klein threatened it with a public inquiry in 1986.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Thus, Frank King remained as CEO, but with the addition of more full-time staff.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Also, more than 9,000 volunteers were registered who were allocated to the most diverse areas.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Despite these changes, there was still some animosity within OCO'88.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Kevin Walmsley noted that Bill Pratt and Frank King continued to have a very tense relationship and that any movement caused sparks with each other.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The 1988 Winter Olympic Games coincided with a shift in television policy by the International Olympic Committee and growing enthusiasm by broadcasters in the United States.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Amendments to the *Olympic Charter* in 1977 established a policy mandating joint television rights involving the IOC and the local organizing committee and was enshrined in the 1981 bid agreement for the Calgary games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The joint negotiating committee convened in 1984 late-January, some weeks before the Sarajevo 1984 Winter Games at the IOC's president residency at the Lausanne Palace were held to negotiate the Calgary television contracts with American broadcasters.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The negotiating committee was represented by Dick Pound for the IOC, Bill Wardle for OCO'88 and consultant Barry Frank.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The co-negotiating committee designed a new tender process for the television rights bid with an emphasis on creating a level playing field for all broadcasters.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] For the first time, the negotiations were based on a series of sealed bids and representatives from ABC, CBS and NBC vied for the opportunity to broadcast the Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] After six rounds of sealed bids, the ABC delegation led by producer Roone Arledge was successful with an agreement paying a record US$309 million (CA$386 million Canadian at the time) in exchange for exclusive rights for the games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] CBS exited the bidding process after the second round with a final offer of $257 million, while ABC and NBC both reached the fifth round with an offer of $300 million.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In the sixth and final stage, the IOC and OCO'88 decided a coin flip would determine which of ABC or NBC had the right to submit the first bid or defer, a decision neither network supported.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Watson elected to call the coin-flip, although he remained silent on the first flip, so a second coinflip was required, and NBC won with a choice of "heads", and after 30 minutes of deliberation submitted a $304 million bid.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] ABC's representative Arledge made a quick phone call to executive Fred Pierce, and ABC submitted a $309 million bid, exceeding NBC's bid by $5 million.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] ABC's record-setting bid was immediately controversial, first Arledge had exceeded the maximum allowable bid set by ABC's executives by $34 million, and in the coming weeks ABC's coverage of the 1984 Winter Olympics which cost $91.5 million returned poor Nielsen ratings.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Early estimates speculated the network would lose $50-$60 million televising the games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] *The Wall Street Journal* described the NBC agreement as the "biggest prize of the Winter Olympics".
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The deal which was at the time the highest amount ever paid for a sporting event, allowed OCO'88 to announce the Games would be debt-free.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The negotiations with American television broadcasters were in sharp contrast to negotiations for Western European rights with the European Broadcasting Union quickly closing an exclusive deal with the IOC for US$5.7 million led by Juan Antonio Samaranch and Marc Hodler on behalf of the IOC.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The *Calgary Herald* headline after the announcement negatively reflected on the "bargain" the European network received, and OCO'88 chairman Frank King publicly expressed his disappointment with the IOC.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Samaranch's argument for providing for a privileged negotiation with EBU was ensuring European viewers had equal access and coverage of the games, something he did not believe would occur if private networks from each nation were provided with the opportunity to bid.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Dick Pound was also critical of the decision and argued more revenue could be brought in from BBC and RAI alone and the privileged status suppressed the willingness of the EBU to make a market-value bid on the games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The CTV Television Network won the bid to broadcast the Games in Canada in December 1983, paying CA$4.5 million for the exclusive rights.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] CTV also won the $23.5 million contract to serve as the host broadcaster, responsible for the manpower and equipment to televise the games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In 1978, while the bid was strengthened, CBC and CTV signed an agreement that if Calgary were the eventual winner, the two broadcasters would create a consortium in which the purchase of television rights would take place jointly.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The previous arrangement had CBC provide full coverage for Summer Games with CTV broadcasting a nightly summary, while CTV had the rights to Winter Games with CBC broadcasting a nightly summary.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The nightly summary of the Games was also televised on CBC.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Japan's broadcast rights were awarded to NHK in July 1986 for US$3.9 million.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] OCO'88 made several alterations to the Olympic program as part of efforts to ensure value for its broadcast partners.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Now, the premier and main events, including ice hockey and figure skating, were scheduled for prime time and the Games were lengthened to 15 days from the previous 12 to ensure three weekends of coverage.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] However, a significant downturn in advertising revenue for sporting events resulted in ABC forecasting significant financial losses on the Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Calgary organizers appreciated their fortunate timing in signing the deal.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] King described the timing of the contract with ABC as "the passing of the sun and the moon at the right time for Calgary".
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The revenue growth from broadcasting was significant for the Calgary Games, OCO'88 generated $324.9 million in broadcast rights, which was a significant growth over an eight-period (the 1980 Lake Placid Games generated US$20.7 million).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] ABC had net losses of more than $60 million, and broadcast rights to the 1992 Winter Olympics were later sold to the CBS network for $243 million, a 20 per cent reduction compared to Calgary.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] A series of ticket-related scandals plagued the organizing committee as the Games approached, resulting in widespread public anger.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Demand for tickets was high, particularly for the main events which had sold out a year in advance.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Residents had been promised that only 10 per cent of tickets would go to "Olympic insiders", IOC officials and sponsors, but OCO'88 was later forced to admit that up to 50 percent of seats to top events had gone to insiders.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The organizing committee, which was subsequently chastised by mayor Klein for running a "closed shop", admitted that it had failed to properly communicate the obligations it had to supply IOC officials and sponsors with priority tickets.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] At that time, the American dollar was trading 40 cents higher than the Canadian dollar, resulting in significantly higher than anticipated revenue through currency conversion.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The ticket manager maintained his innocence claiming he was used as a scapegoat and sponsor credit card Visa was responsible for the error, despite his claims, the ticketing manager was convicted of fraud, theft, and forgery, and sentenced to 5 years in prison.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Organizers attempted to respond to public concern by asking sponsors to consider reducing their orders and by paying $1.5 million to add 2,600 seats to the Saddledome, as well as increase capacity for ski jumping, alpine skiing and the opening ceremonies.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] This led to a change of the venue of the closing ceremonies from Saddledome to McMahon Stadium, as the stadium capacity was about two times bigger than the indoor venue.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] King also noted that the Calgary Games offered a then-record 1.9 million tickets for sale, three times the amount available at Sarajevo or Lake Placid and that 79 percent of them were to be allocated to Calgarians.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] By the start of the 1988 Winter Games, a record of over 1.4 million tickets had been sold, a figure that eclipsed the previous three Winter Games combined.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In the OCO'88's final report, the Committee admits the culmination of fraud charges, a large portion of premier tickets requested by Olympic insiders, and poor communications led to a negative public reaction to the ticketing process.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] For the first time in the history of the Olympics, both summer and winter, the Organizing Committee worked with a refund policy for returned or unused tickets.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] When an event was postponed by at least 24 hours, the ticketholder was eligible for a refund.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Due to weather issues, the 8 events that were scheduled for the first 24 hours had to be rescheduled, resulting in 130,000 ticket refunds totalling CA$2.9 million, with transactions handled by the Royal Bank of Canada.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The city of Calgary is world-renowned for the enthusiasm of its population for volunteer work which is reflected in the annual Calgary Stampede, which also relied heavily on volunteers to run the Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Over 22,000 people signed up for more than 9,400 positions, no matter how inglorious: doctors, lawyers and executives even offered to collect the waste generated during the opening ceremony.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Also, for the first time, a "Homestay" program was created and several local families opened their homes to visitors from around the world, and others were renting their rooms or houses to those who could not stay in pay a reserve in a hotel.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Klein was among those who felt it necessary that the event be community driven, a decision which allowed the city's welcoming spirit to manifest.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Games' mascots, Hidy and Howdy, were designed to evoke images of "western hospitality".
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The smiling, cowboy-themed polar bears were popular across Canada.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Played by a team of 150 students from Bishop Carroll High School, the sister-brother pair made up to 300 appearances per month in the lead-up to the Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] From their introduction at the closing ceremonies of the Sarajevo Games in 1984 until their retirement at the conclusion of the Calgary Games, the pair made about 50,000 appearances.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The iconic mascots graced signs welcoming travellers to Calgary for nearly two decades until they were replaced in 2007.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The mascot's names "Hidy" and "Howdy" were chosen by a public contest.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The 1988 Winter Olympic Games were the most expensive Games, summer or winter, to be held at that time, with total expenses exceeding CA$879.6 million.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The high cost was anticipated, as organizers were aware at the outset of their bid that most facilities would have to be constructed.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The venues, constructed primarily with public money, were designed to have lasting use beyond the Games and were planned to become the home of several of Canada's national winter sports teams.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The record-breaking cost of the Calgary Olympics came in stark contrast to the original projections during the 1981 bid, which estimated a total cost of CA$218 million, split between CA$126 million in capital costs and CA$92 million in operating costs.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The significant growth in capital expenditures came despite the three levels of government taking over projects which constituted nearly half of the original budgeted capital projects.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Of the total expenses for the Games (CA$879.6 million), the Government of Canada contributed CA$200 million (22.7 per cent), the Government of Alberta contributed CA$130 million (14.8 per cent), and the City of Calgary contributed CA$43 million (4.9 per cent).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The CA$320.8 million of government capital contributions not directly included in OCO'88's revenue statements included the Government of Canada constructing the CA$72.2 million Canada Olympic Park, and CA$40 million for the Olympic Oval.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Provincial expenses included CA$14.4 million to build the Canmore Nordic Centre, and CA$25.3 million to build Nakiska.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] All three governments contributed to the CA$97.7 million Olympic Saddledome.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Games were a major economic boom for the city, which had fallen into its worst recession in 40 years following the collapse of both oil and grain prices three years before the games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] A report prepared for the city in January 1985 estimated the games would create 11,100 man-years of employment and generate CA$450 million in salaries and wages.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In its post-Games report, OCO'88 estimated the Olympics created CA$1.4 billion in economic benefits across Canada during the 1980s, 70 percent within Alberta, as a result of capital spending, increased tourism and new sporting opportunities created by the facilities.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The 1988 Olympic torch relay began on November 15, 1987, when the torch was lit at Olympia and Greek runner Stelios Bisbas began what was called "the longest torch run in history".
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] John's, Newfoundland on the Atlantic Ocean two days later and over 88 days, travelled west across the then 10 Canadian provinces and two territories.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It passed through most major cities, north to the Arctic Ocean at Inuvik, Northwest Territories, then west to the Pacific Ocean at Victoria, British Columbia before returning east to Alberta, and finally Calgary.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The torch covered a distance of 18,000 kilometres (11,000 mi), the greatest distance for a torch relay in Olympic history until the 2000 Sydney Games, and a sharp contrast to the 1976 Montreal Games when the relay covered only 775 kilometres (482 mi).
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The identity of the final torchbearer who would light the Olympic cauldron was one of the Organizing Committee's most closely guarded secrets.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] John's with Barbara Ann Scott and Ferd Hayward representing Canada's past Olympians and ended with Ken Read and Cathy Priestner carrying the torch into McMahon Stadium representing the nation's current Olympians.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The design of the Olympic Torch for the Calgary games was a reproduction of the main landmark building of the Calgary skyline, the Calgary Tower.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The National Research Council Canada developed the design for the Torch, the base of the torch is made of maple wood, the national tree of Canada, aluminum, and hardened steel, all 100% collected in Canadian territory.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The torch was designed to remain lit despite the extreme conditions of Canadian winters.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Torch had to be light enough for relay runners to carry comfortably, and the final design came in at 60 centimetres in length and 1.7 kilograms in weight.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The maple handle portion included laser-incised pictograms of the 10 official Olympic Winter sports, and lettering was engraved on the steel caldron portion.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The torch used a mixed type of three fuels (gasoline, kerosene and alcohol) to allow a continuous burn during the unpredictable Canadian winter.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Approximately 100 torches were manufactured for the Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Governor General Jeanne Sauvé opened the Games on behalf of Queen Elizabeth II as an estimated 1.5 billion people watched the ceremony.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The weather was a dominant story throughout much of the Games, as strong chinook winds that brought daily temperatures as high as 17 °C (63 °F) wreaked havoc on the schedules for outdoor events.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Events were delayed when winds were deemed unsafe for competitors and organizers used artificial snow making equipment to ensure skiing venues were properly prepared.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] It was the first time in Olympic history that alpine events were held on artificial snow.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Games were also marred by the death of the Austrian ski team's doctor, Joerg Oberhammer, on February 25 after a collision with another skier threw him underneath a working snow grooming machine at Nakiska, crushing and killing him instantly.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The top individual competitors at the Olympics were Finnish ski jumper Matti Nykänen and Dutch speed skater Yvonne van Gennip as they each won three gold medals.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Italy's Alberto Tomba won gold in two skiing events, his first of five career Olympic medals en route to becoming the first alpine skier to win medals at three Winter Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] East Germany's Katarina Witt defended her 1984 gold medal in women's figure skating, capturing a second gold in Calgary.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Her compatriot Christa Rothenburger won the gold medal in the 1000 metre race in speed skating, then went on to win a silver medal in the team sprint cycling event at the 1988 Summer Games to become the only person in Olympic history to win medals at both Olympic Games in the same year.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Soviet Union won gold in ice hockey as Nordic neighbours Finland and Sweden took silver and bronze, respectively.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] As it had in 1976, Canada again failed to win an official gold medal as the host of an Olympic Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Canadians won two gold medals in demonstration events, including by Sylvie Daigle as one of her five medals in short-track speed skating.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Canada's top official performances came in figure skating where Brian Orser and Elizabeth Manley each won silver medals.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Boitano won the gold medal over Orser by one-tenth of a point.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Witt won the gold while Thomas won the bronze medal.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Manley was not viewed as a medal contender, but skated the greatest performance of her career to come within a fraction of Witt's gold medal-winning score.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] American speed skater Dan Jansen's personal tragedy was one of the more poignant events of the Games as he skated the 500 metre race mere hours after his sister Jane died of leukemia.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] A gold medal favourite, Jansen chose to compete as he felt it is what his sister would have wanted.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Viewers around the world witnessed his heartbreak as he fell and crashed into the outer wall in the first quarter of his heat.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] In the 1000 metre race four days later, Jansen was on a world record pace when he again fell.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] After failing again in Albertville, Jansen finally won a gold medal at the 1994 Lillehamer Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] One of the most popular athletes from the games was British ski jumper Michael Edwards, who gained infamy by placing last in both the 70 and 90 metre events finishing 70 and 53 points behind his next closest competitor, respectively.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Edwards' "heroic failure" made him an instant celebrity; he went from earning £6,000 per year as a plasterer before the Games to making £10,000 per hour per appearance afterward.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Left embarrassed by the spectacle he created, the IOC altered the rules following Calgary to eliminate each nation's right to send at least one athlete and set minimum competition standards for future events.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Regardless, the President of the Organizing Committee, Frank King, playfully saluted Edwards' unorthodox sporting legacy, which would also be commemorated with a 2016 feature film, *Eddie the Eagle*.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The Jamaican bobsleigh team, making their nation's Winter Olympic debut, was also popular in Calgary.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The team was the brainchild of a pair of Americans who recruited individuals with strong sprinting ability from the Jamaican military to form the team.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Dudley Stokes and Michael White finished the two-man event in 30th place out of 41 competitors and launched the Jamaican team into worldwide fame.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] The pair, along with Devon Harris and Chris Stokes, crashed in the four-man event, but were met with cheers from the crowd as they pushed their sled across the finish line.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] Their odyssey was made into the 1993 movie *Cool Runnings*, a largely fictionalized comedy by Walt Disney Pictures.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p01] All of the long track world (WR) and Olympic records (OR) that occurred during these Games were later broken at succeeding Winter Olympics and other world events.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Prior to 1988, the Winter Olympics were viewed as a second-rate event, in comparison to the Summer Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] The IOC had, at one point, considered eliminating it altogether.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] First, there are only a few mountainous areas in the world that would be able to host the Winter Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Second, there were major challenges in generating revenues for the host city and the IOC from such Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] However, CODA convinced the IOC that it could not only generate enough revenues to make a profit but have enough money left over to ensure a lasting legacy of winter sports development.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] OCO'88 followed mainly the example of LAOOC which organized the 1984 Summer Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Under LAOOC's president, Peter Ueberroth, he was able to attract a large United States television contract and Los Angeles became the first Olympic host city to make a profit.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] For the 1988 Winter Olympics, OCO'88 attracted financial support from over two dozen major Canadian and multinational corporations, in order to generate millions of dollars in revenues.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] For OCO'88, it foresaw some winter sports, like the debut of the Super-G and other new winter sports events, as a way to increase the audience's appeal of the Winter Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Thus, for the sponsors, the Games' length of time to 15 days provided an extra weekend of Olympic media coverage to the world.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] This additional programming time was filled mainly by TV-friendly demonstration events that are popular in Canada.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] The 1988 Winter Olympics' exposure to curling, freestyle skiing, and short track speed skating events in Calgary influenced the worldwide popularity of all of them.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] So much so that all these events became the new and official Olympic finals in the period between the 1992 Winter Olympics to the 2002 Winter Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Hosting the Winter Olympics helped fuel a significant increase in Calgary's reputation on the world stage.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Crosbie Cotton, a reporter for the *Calgary Herald* who covered the city's Olympic odyssey from its 1979 initiative to the closing ceremonies, noted an increased positive outlook of the city's population over time.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] He believed that the populace began to outgrow its "giant inferiority complex" that is "typically Canadian", by replacing it with a new level of confidence as the Games approached.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] This outcome helped the city grow from a regional oil and gas centre, best known for the Calgary Stampede, to a destination for international political, economic, and sporting events.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] A study prepared for the organizing committee of the 2010 Winter Olympics, (VANOC), claimed that Calgary hosted over 200 national and international sporting competitions between 1987 and 2007, due to the facilities it had constructed for these Olympic Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] The Games' enduring popularity within Calgary has been attributed to efforts in making them "everybody's Games." Aside from the sense of community fostered by the high level of volunteer support, OCO'88 included the general public in other ways.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] For example, the citizens were given an opportunity to purchase a brick with their names engraved on it.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Those bricks were used to build the Olympic Plaza, where the medal ceremonies were held in 1988.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] It remains a popular public park and event site in the city's downtown core today.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] After the success of these Olympic Games, Calgary was wanting to bring back the Olympic experience again.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] It offered, to the IOC, in becoming a possible alternate host city of the 2002 Winter Olympics, after a bidding scandal resulted in speculation that Salt Lake City would not be able to remain the host city.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Next, the city was attempting to be Canada's bid for the 2010 Winter Olympics, but the COC decided to give it to Vancouver and Whistler.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Later, a 2013 *Calgary Sun* online poll found that 81% of respondents said they would support the idea of hosting another Winter Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] On November 13, 2018, Calgary held a public non-binding plebiscite on whether it should bid to host the 2026 Olympic and Paralympic Winter Games.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] On November 19, 2018, the results of the plebiscite showed that 56.4% (171,750) of eligible voters said "No", while 43.6% (132,832) of them said "Yes." Therefore, the city council concluded that the bid would be withdrawn.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] In light of the 1976 Summer Olympics' disastrous financial legacy, the Calgary Olympic organizing committee, OCO'88, parlayed its ability to generate television and sponsorship revenues, along with the three levels of government support, into what was ultimately a C$170 million surplus.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] While OCO'88 reported officially a surplus after the Games were over, the accounting practices of the final report did not include federal, provincial, and municipal capital and operations funding infrastructures.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] The overall surplus was turned into endowment funds that were split between Canada Olympic Park (C$110 million) and CODA.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] They were subsequently reformed later, in order to manage the Olympic facilities with a trust fund that had grown steadily to be worth over C$200 million by 2013.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Consequently, all five primary facilities built for the 1988 Winter Olympics remained operational for their intended purposes, 25 years after the Games concluded.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Calgary and Canmore became the heart of winter sports in Canada, as CODA (now known as WinSport) established itself as the nation's leader in developing elite winter athletes.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] For the 2006 Winter Olympics, a quarter of Canada's Olympic winter athletes were from the Calgary region and three-quarters of its medalists were from or trained in Alberta.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Before 1988, Canada was not a winter sports power.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] The nation's five overall medals won in Calgary was its second-best total at a Winter Olympics, behind the seven overall medals it won at the 1932 Winter Olympics in Lake Placid, New York.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] After 1988, Canada won an increasing number of gold and overall medals at each successive Winter Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] It culminated in an overall performance of 26 medals won at the 2010 Winter Olympics, which included the previous Olympic record of 14 gold medals.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] Until 2010, Norway won the most Olympic gold medals on home soil at the 1952 Winter Olympics.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] However, Norway recaptured the record of winning the most Olympic gold medals at a single Winter Olympics in 2022, claiming 16.
[src:1988-winter-olympics/1988-winter-olympics-p02] At the 2018 Winter Olympics, Canada earned its highest overall medal count in the Winter Olympics to date, with a total of 29 medals.
